{"title_page": "A Separate Creation", "text_new": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation\n| image = A Separate Creation.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| author = [[Chandler Burr]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Sexual orientation]]\n| publisher = [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion]]\n| pub_date = 1996\n| media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]])\n| pages = 354\n| isbn = 978-0786882403\n}}\n'''''A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation''''', also published with the subtitle '''''How Biology Makes Us Gay''''', is a 1996 book about the development of [[sexual orientation]] by the journalist [[Chandler Burr]]. It received mainly positive reviews, commending it as a useful discussion of scientific research on sexual orientation and the politics surrounding the issue.\n\n==Summary==\n{{expand section|date=October 2018}}\nBurr discusses biological research on [[sexual orientation]] by scientists such as the neuroscientist [[Simon LeVay]], the psychiatrist [[Richard Pillard]], the psychologists [[J. Michael Bailey]], [[Heino Meyer-Bahlburg]], and [[Anke Ehrhardt]], and the geneticist [[Dean Hamer]]. He writes that a neuroanatomical study published in 1991 was the \"first major biological investigation of sexual orientation\", and that it was followed by research into genes and hormones. He also discusses the views of critics of the research, such as the evolutionary biologist [[Richard Lewontin]].{{sfn|Burr|1996|pages=3\u20134, 270}}\n\n==Publication history==\n''A Separate Creation'' was published by [[Hachette Books|Hyperion]] in 1996, under the full title ''A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation''.{{sfn|Burr|1996|pages=iii\u2013iv}} The book was published as ''A Separate Creation: How Biology Makes Us Gay'' by [[Bantam Press]] in 1997.{{sfn|Burr|1996|page=iv}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Mainstream media===\n''A Separate Creation'' received positive reviews from Ray Olson in ''[[Booklist]]'',{{sfn|Olson|1996|page=1466}} Genevieve Stuttaford in ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'',{{sfn|Stuttaford|1996|page=65}} the neurologist [[Richard Cytowic]] in ''[[The Washington Post]]'',{{sfn|Cytowic|1996|page=9}} the historian [[Jonathan Kirsch]] in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',{{sfn|Kirsch|1996}} the philosopher [[Michael Ruse]] in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'',{{sfn|Ruse|1996|page=14}} and W. P. Anderson in ''Choice'',{{sfn|Anderson|1996|page=481}} a mixed review from Gail Vines in ''[[New Scientist]]'',{{sfn|Vines|1996|page=41}} and a negative review from the historian [[Roy Porter]] in ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]''.{{sfn|Porter|1996}} The book was also reviewed by Jon Turney in the ''[[Times Higher Education|Times Higher Education Supplement]]'',{{sfn|Turney|1997|page=22}} and discussed by [[Norman Podhoretz]] in ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]''.{{sfn|Podhoretz|1996|page=37}}\n\nOlson credited Burr with writing about science well and with covering the arguments of both supporters and critics of biological explanations of sexual orientation and the associated political issues. He suggested that the arguments of scientists who think some findings are \"either not so significant, misleading, or downright erroneous\" were often more convincing than those of scientists on the other side of the debate. He concluded that ''A Separate Creation'' might be \"both the gay studies book of the year and the popular-science book of the year.\"{{sfn|Olson|1996|page=1466}} Stuttaford described the book as a \"detailed, elegantly written report\" on scientific research on sexual orientation, crediting Burr with dispassionately reviewing the scientific and political controversy created by LeVay's 1991 hypothalamus study.{{sfn|Stuttaford|1996|page=65}} Cytowic credited Burr with \"disclosing the political meaning of sexual-orientation research\" and with \"revealing the media's absurd questions and abysmal grasp of science.\"{{sfn|Cytowic|1996|page=9}} Kirsch called the book \"enlightening\" and an \"earnest and mostly successful\" effort to explain the findings of genetic research. He credited Burr with providing a \"compelling profile\" of the scientists involved in sexual orientation research and with explaining the politics of the issue.{{sfn|Kirsch|1996}}\n\nRuse considered ''A Separate Creation'' a good discussion of its topic. He noted that it had appeared at the same time as several other books about biological research on homosexuality, suggesting that this showed that \"publishers know a good thing when they see it.\"{{sfn|Ruse|1996|page=14}} Anderson wrote that Burr provided an \"absorbing and comprehensive\" discussion of biological research on sexual orientation, and a clearly written \"reader-friendly interpretation\" of the topic, with a broad presentation of recent findings. He concluded that ''A Separate Creation'' would be interesting to both scientists and the general public.{{sfn|Anderson|1996|page=481}} Vines described ''A Separate Creation'' as a \"racy paean to the putative gay gene\" and \"a masterpiece of American journalese\". She wrote that ''A Separate Creation'' contained \"little analysis and lots of hype\", but credited Burr with speaking to many researchers interested in searching for a biological basis to homosexuality, and concluded that the book was worth reading, \"If you can stomach this sort of thing\".{{sfn|Vines|1996|page=41}} Porter called ''A Separate Creation'' a dispiriting comment on the state of science, writing that sexual orientation researchers have made exaggerated claims based on limited and sometimes flawed evidence.{{sfn|Porter|1996}}\n\nPodhoretz described the book as a \"breathless account\" of its topic.{{sfn|Podhoretz|1996|page=37}}\n\n===Gay media===\n''A Separate Creation'' received a positive review from the physician [[Lawrence D. Mass]] in ''Lambda Book Report''.{{sfn|Mass|1996|page=14}} The book was also reviewed by Stephen H. Miller in the ''[[New York Native]]''.{{sfn|Miller|1996|page=18}} An excerpt appeared in ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]''.{{sfn|McAuley|1996|page=35}} Burr's \"Gay Gene\" website, based on his book, was listed as a \"hot web site\" by ''The Advocate'' in 1998.{{sfn|Haeberli|1998|page=18}} Tom Moon discussed Burr's views in the ''[[San Francisco Bay Times]]''.{{sfn|Moon|2006|page=11}}\n\nMass considered Burr a \"gay-positive essentialist\" and ''A Separate Creation'' \"a valuable historical document\" comparable to the journalist [[Randy Shilts]]' ''[[And the Band Played On]]'' (1987).{{sfn|Mass|1996|page=14}}\n\n===Other evaluations and responses===\nRon Good and Mark Hafner discussed ''A Separate Creation'' in ''[[The American Biology Teacher]]''.{{sfn|Good|Hafner|2000|page=326}}\n\nThe feminist [[Germaine Greer]] and the evolutionary biologist [[Marlene Zuk]] praised ''A Separate Creation''.{{sfn|Greer|1999|page=344}}{{sfn|Zuk|2002|page=218}} However, the book was criticized by the philosophers Timothy F. Murphy and Edward Stein.{{sfn|Murphy|1997|page=238}}{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=166, 350}} Murphy wrote that that Burr incorrectly stated that LeVay's 1991 neuroanatomical report on the hypothalamus was the first major biological investigation of sexual orientation. He noted that scientific study of the determinants of sexual orientation dates to the 19th century and that many investigations of the possible biological basis of homosexuality preceded LeVay's work.{{sfn|Murphy|1997|page=238}} Stein, who noted that Burr was a journalist by background, called him \"unsophisticated\" for failing to discuss [[Social constructionism|social constructionist]] views and accepting claims about the factors that cause homosexuality in fruit flies, including the discovery of a single gene that supposedly controls courtship behavior between male flies. He argued that such animal research commits the fallacy of [[anthropomorphism]] and is irrelevant to understanding sexual orientation in humans.{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=166, 350}}\n\nThe psychologist Louis A. Berman described Burr's evaluation of the biological evidence as optimistic. Berman, who believes that writers supportive of gay rights have ignored professional literature dealing with efforts to change sexual orientation, noted in this connexion that though Burr conducted a two-hour interview with the psychoanalyst [[Charles Socarides]], Burr does not mention this.{{sfn|Berman|2003|page=511}} According to Burr, his argument that in ''A Separate Creation'' that sexual orientation is innate prompted a call by Southern Baptists to boycott Disney films and theme parks because the book was published by Hyperion, a subsidiary of [[The Walt Disney Company]].{{sfn|Burr|2015}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Biology and sexual orientation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n;Books\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Berman |first1=Louis A. |title=The Puzzle: Exploring the Evolutionary Puzzle of Male Homosexuality |publisher=Godot Press |location=Wilmette, Illinois |year=2003 |isbn=0-9723013-1-3 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/puzzleexploringe0000berm }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Burr|first1=Chandler |title=A Separate Creation: How Biology Makes Us Gay |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |location=New York |year=1997 |isbn=0-553-40728-7 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Burr |first1=Chandler |title=A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation |publisher=[[Hachette Books|Hyperion]] |location=New York |year=1996 |isbn=0-78-68-6081-2 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/separatecreation00burr }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Greer|first1=Germaine |title=The Whole Woman |publisher=[[Transworld Publishers]] |location=London |year=1999 |isbn=0-385-60016-X |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Murphy|first1=Timothy F. |title=Gay Science: The Ethics of Sexual Orientation Research |url=https://archive.org/details/gayscienceethics0000murp|url-access=registration|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] |location=New York |year=1997 |isbn=0-231-10849-4 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Stein |first1=Edward |title=The Mismeasure of Desire: The Science, Theory, and Ethics of Sexual Orientation |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Berkeley |year=1999 |isbn=0-19-514244-6 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/mismeasureofdesi00stei_0 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Zuk|first1=Marlene |title=Sexual Selections: What We Can and Can't Learn About Sex from Animals |url=https://archive.org/details/sexualselections0000zukm|url-access=registration|publisher=[[University of California Press]] |location=Berkeley |year=2002 |isbn=0-520-21974-0 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Journals\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |title=A separate creation (Book Review) |last1=Anderson|first1=W. P. |journal=Choice |volume=34 |issue= |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=All in the genes |last1=Cytowic|first1=Richard E. |journal=[[The Washington Post]] |volume=119 |issue=271 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Scientific Understanding of Sexual Orientation: Implications for Science Education |last1=Good|first1=Ron |last2=Hafner|first2=Mark |journal=[[The American Biology Teacher]] |volume=62 |issue=5 |year=2000 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Hot Web site |last1=Haeberli|first1=Eric |journal=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |volume= |issue=768 |year=1998 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Born gay? |last1=Mass|first1=Lawrence D. |journal=Lambda Book Report |volume=5 |issue=1 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Hunting homosexuality |last1=McAuley|first1=J. V. |journal=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |volume= |issue=709 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Dissenting Voices |last1=Miller|first1=Stephen H. |journal=[[New York Native]] |volume= |issue=692 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Is it Learned or Biological? |last1=Moon|first1=Tom |journal=[[San Francisco Bay Times]] |volume= |issue=August 10, 2006 |year=2006 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Upfront: Advance reviews |last1=Olson|first1=Ray |journal=[[Booklist]] |volume=92 |issue=17 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=How the Gay-Rights Movement Won |last1=Podhoretz|first1=Norman |journal=[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]] |volume=102 |issue= |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Glad to be gay? |last1=Ruse|first1=Michael |journal=[[The Times Literary Supplement]] |volume= |issue=4883 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Forecasts: Nonfiction |last1=Stuttaford|first1=Genevieve |journal=[[Publishers Weekly]] |volume=243 |issue=20 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Biology to sway the Vatican? |last1=Turney|first1=Jon |journal=[[Times Higher Education|The Times Higher Education Supplement]] |volume= |issue=1280 |year=1997 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Pride and prejudice |last1=Vines|first1=Gail |journal=[[New Scientist]] |volume=151 |issue=2038 |year=1996 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Online articles\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Burr|first1=Chandler |url = http://www.chandlerburr.com/bio.htm | title = About Chandler |date=2015 |work=Chandler Burr's website |accessdate = 4 January 2017 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Kirsch|first1=Jonathan |url = http://articles.latimes.com/1996-10-02/news/ls-49490_1_sexual-orientation | title = The 'Gay Gene' and the Politics Surrounding It : A SEPARATE CREATION: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation, by Chandler Burr (Hyperion; $24.95, 354 pages) |date=October 2, 1996 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate = 8 February 2017 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Porter|first1=Roy |url = https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/07/27/nnp/19945.html | title = Born That Way? |date=August 11, 1996 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate = 14 September 2013 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Separate Creation, A}}\n[[Category:1996 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books by Chandler Burr]]\n[[Category:English-language books]]\n[[Category:Hyperion Books books]]\n[[Category:LGBT non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Popular psychology books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation\n| image = A Separate Creation.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| author = [[Chandler Burr]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Sexual orientation]]\n| publisher = [[Hyperion Books|Hyperion]]\n| pub_date = 1996\n| media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]])\n| pages = 354\n| isbn = 978-0786882403\n}}\n'''''A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation''''', also published with the subtitle '''''How Biology Makes Us Gay''''', is a 1996 book about the development of [[sexual orientation]] by the journalist [[Chandler Burr]]. It received mainly positive reviews, commending it as a useful discussion of scientific research on sexual orientation and the politics surrounding the issue.\n\n==Summary==\n{{expand section|date=October 2018}}\nBurr discusses biological research on [[sexual orientation]] by scientists such as the neuroscientist [[Simon LeVay]], the psychiatrist [[Richard Pillard]], the psychologists [[J. Michael Bailey]], [[Heino Meyer-Bahlburg]], and [[Anke Ehrhardt]], and the geneticist [[Dean Hamer]]. He writes that a neuroanatomical study published in 1991 was the \"first major biological investigation of sexual orientation\", and that it was followed by research into genes and hormones. He also discusses the views of critics of the research, such as the evolutionary biologist [[Richard Lewontin]].{{sfn|Burr|1996|pages=3\u20134, 270}}\n\n==Publication history==\n''A Separate Creation'' was published by [[Hachette Books|Hyperion]] in 1996, under the full title ''A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation''.{{sfn|Burr|1996|pages=iii\u2013iv}} The book was published as ''A Separate Creation: How Biology Makes Us Gay'' by [[Bantam Press]] in 1997.{{sfn|Burr|1996|page=iv}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Mainstream media===\n''A Separate Creation'' received positive reviews from Ray Olson in ''[[Booklist]]'',{{sfn|Olson|1996|page=1466}} Genevieve Stuttaford in ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'',{{sfn|Stuttaford|1996|page=65}} the neurologist [[Richard Cytowic]] in ''[[The Washington Post]]'',{{sfn|Cytowic|1996|page=9}} the historian [[Jonathan Kirsch]] in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',{{sfn|Kirsch|1996}} the philosopher [[Michael Ruse]] in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'',{{sfn|Ruse|1996|page=14}} and W. P. Anderson in ''Choice'',{{sfn|Anderson|1996|page=481}} a mixed review from Gail Vines in ''[[New Scientist]]'',{{sfn|Vines|1996|page=41}} and a negative review from the historian [[Roy Porter]] in ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]''.{{sfn|Porter|1996}} The book was also reviewed by Jon Turney in the ''[[Times Higher Education|Times Higher Education Supplement]]'',{{sfn|Turney|1997|page=22}} and discussed by [[Norman Podhoretz]] in ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]''.{{sfn|Podhoretz|1996|page=37}}\n\nOlson credited Burr with writing about science well and with covering the arguments of both supporters and critics of biological explanations of sexual orientation and the associated political issues. He suggested that the arguments of scientists who think some findings are \"either not so significant, misleading, or downright erroneous\" were often more convincing than those of scientists on the other side of the debate. He concluded that ''A Separate Creation'' might be \"both the gay studies book of the year and the popular-science book of the year.\"{{sfn|Olson|1996|page=1466}} Stuttaford described the book as a \"detailed, elegantly written report\" on scientific research on sexual orientation, crediting Burr with dispassionately reviewing the scientific and political controversy created by LeVay's 1991 hypothalamus study.{{sfn|Stuttaford|1996|page=65}} Cytowic credited Burr with \"disclosing the political meaning of sexual-orientation research\" and with \"revealing the media's absurd questions and abysmal grasp of science.\"{{sfn|Cytowic|1996|page=9}} Kirsch called the book \"enlightening\" and an \"earnest and mostly successful\" effort to explain the findings of genetic research. He credited Burr with providing a \"compelling profile\" of the scientists involved in sexual orientation research and with explaining the politics of the issue.{{sfn|Kirsch|1996}}\n\nRuse considered ''A Separate Creation'' a good discussion of its topic. He noted that it had appeared at the same time as several other books about biological research on homosexuality, suggesting that this showed that \"publishers know a good thing when they see it.\"{{sfn|Ruse|1996|page=14}} Anderson wrote that Burr provided an \"absorbing and comprehensive\" discussion of biological research on sexual orientation, and a clearly written \"reader-friendly interpretation\" of the topic, with a broad presentation of recent findings. He concluded that ''A Separate Creation'' would be interesting to both scientists and the general public.{{sfn|Anderson|1996|page=481}} Vines described ''A Separate Creation'' as a \"racy paean to the putative gay gene\" and \"a masterpiece of American journalese\". She wrote that ''A Separate Creation'' contained \"little analysis and lots of hype\", but credited Burr with speaking to many researchers interested in searching for a biological basis to homosexuality, and concluded that the book was worth reading, \"If you can stomach this sort of thing\".{{sfn|Vines|1996|page=41}} Porter called ''A Separate Creation'' a dispiriting comment on the state of science, writing that sexual orientation researchers have made exaggerated claims based on limited and sometimes flawed evidence.{{sfn|Porter|1996}}\n\nPodhoretz described the book as a \"breathless account\" of its topic.{{sfn|Podhoretz|1996|page=37}}\n\n===Gay media===\n''A Separate Creation'' received a positive review from the physician [[Lawrence D. Mass]] in ''Lambda Book Report''.{{sfn|Mass|1996|page=14}} The book was also reviewed by Stephen H. Miller in the ''[[New York Native]]''.{{sfn|Miller|1996|page=18}} An excerpt appeared in ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]''.{{sfn|McAuley|1996|page=35}} Burr's \"Gay Gene\" website, based on his book, was listed as a \"hot web site\" by ''The Advocate'' in 1998.{{sfn|Haeberli|1998|page=18}} Tom Moon discussed Burr's views in the ''[[San Francisco Bay Times]]''.{{sfn|Moon|2006|page=11}}\n\nMass considered Burr a \"gay-positive essentialist\" and ''A Separate Creation'' \"a valuable historical document\" comparable to the journalist [[Randy Shilts]]' ''[[And the Band Played On]]'' (1987).{{sfn|Mass|1996|page=14}}\n\n===Other evaluations and responses===\nRon Good and Mark Hafner discussed ''A Separate Creation'' in ''[[The American Biology Teacher]]''.{{sfn|Good|Hafner|2000|page=326}}\n\nThe feminist [[Germaine Greer]] and the evolutionary biologist [[Marlene Zuk]] praised ''A Separate Creation''.{{sfn|Greer|1999|page=344}}{{sfn|Zuk|2002|page=218}} However, the book was criticized by the philosophers Timothy F. Murphy and Edward Stein.{{sfn|Murphy|1997|page=238}}{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=166, 350}} Murphy wrote that that Burr incorrectly stated that LeVay's 1991 neuroanatomical report on the hypothalamus was the first major biological investigation of sexual orientation. He noted that scientific study of the determinants of sexual orientation dates to the 19th century and that many investigations of the possible biological basis of homosexuality preceded LeVay's work.{{sfn|Murphy|1997|page=238}} Stein, who noted that Burr was a journalist by background, called him \"unsophisticated\" for failing to discuss [[Social constructionism|social constructionist]] views and accepting claims about the factors that cause homosexuality in fruit flies, including the discovery of a single gene that supposedly controls courtship behavior between male flies. He argued that such animal research commits the fallacy of [[anthropomorphism]] and is irrelevant to understanding sexual orientation in humans.{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=166, 350}}\n\nThe psychologist Louis A. Berman described Burr's evaluation of the biological evidence as optimistic. Berman, who believes that writers supportive of gay rights have ignored professional literature dealing with efforts to change sexual orientation, noted in this connexion that though Burr conducted a two-hour interview with the psychoanalyst [[Charles Socarides]], Burr does not mention this.{{sfn|Berman|2003|page=511}} According to Burr, his argument that in ''A Separate Creation'' that sexual orientation is innate prompted a call by Southern Baptists to boycott Disney films and theme parks because the book was published by Hyperion, a subsidiary of [[The Walt Disney Company]].{{sfn|Burr|2015}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Biology and sexual orientation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n;Books\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Berman |first1=Louis A. |title=The Puzzle: Exploring the Evolutionary Puzzle of Male Homosexuality |publisher=Godot Press |location=Wilmette, Illinois |year=2003 |isbn=0-9723013-1-3 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/puzzleexploringe0000berm }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Burr|first1=Chandler |title=A Separate Creation: How Biology Makes Us Gay |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |location=New York |year=1997 |isbn=0-553-40728-7 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Burr |first1=Chandler |title=A Separate Creation: The Search for the Biological Origins of Sexual Orientation |publisher=[[Hachette Books|Hyperion]] |location=New York |year=1996 |isbn=0-78-68-6081-2 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/separatecreation00burr }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Greer|first1=Germaine |title=The Whole Woman |publisher=[[Transworld Publishers]] |location=London |year=1999 |isbn=0-385-60016-X |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Murphy|first1=Timothy F. |title=Gay Science: The Ethics of Sexual Orientation Research |url=https://archive.org/details/gayscienceethics0000murp|url-access=registration|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] |location=New York |year=1997 |isbn=0-231-10849-4 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Stein |first1=Edward |title=The Mismeasure of Desire: The Science, Theory, and Ethics of Sexual Orientation |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Berkeley |year=1999 |isbn=0-19-514244-6 |