ing company for the companies owned by the bank after the financial problems of the 1920s and 1930s, as part of a plan to phase out the bank's ownership of these companies, which included [[L. M. Ericsson]]. The company was named Industriv\u00e4rden (\"The Industry Host\" or \"Industry Values\"), and after the bank's shareholders had been given the opportunity to acquire shares in the holding company, it was listed on the Stockholm Stock Exchange in 1945.<ref name=\"SHB hist\"/>\n\n===1945\u20131970===\nHandelsbanken continued to expand by purchasing other banks in the 1940s and 1950s - V\u00e4nersborgsbanken, Norrk\u00f6pings Folkbank, Lule\u00e5 Folkbank and Gotlandsbanken. The [[mortgage]] company SIGAB was acquired in 1955 and renamed to Handelsbanken Hypotek. In the 1955 to 1965 period, 157 new branch offices were opened, many of these in the newly built suburbs of Stockholm, in order to increase the number of customers and to expand deposits.\n\nTowards the end of the 1960s, the Swedish society saw increased socialist sentiments, just like many other European countries. This was particularly strong among students and other youth, and banks and industrialists in general were portrayed in a very negative way. During this time, Handelsbanken was also the subject of specific criticism from media and authorities, including foreign exchange transactions in 1969 that contravened regulations. The resulting crisis led to the resignation of the bank's management, including CEO Rune H\u00f6glund in 1970.<ref name=\"SHB hist\"/>\n\n===1970\u20131990===\nAfter the resignation of the previous management, Jan Wallander was recruited as the bank's new CEO. Wallander had a background as an economic researcher who had later become CEO of Sundsvallsbanken, a regional bank in northern Sweden. Under Wallander's leadership, many changes were introduced which have continued to be characteristic of Handelsbanken since that time. During 1970\u20131972, Handelsbanken created eight regional banks with a high degree of independence, to which the branch offices belonged. Much of the decision making was decentralised to the local and regional level, and the financial management and control system was overhauled, by focusing more on reporting and less on central budgeting. The new organisation focused on achieving profitability rather than on volume growth, which had been the case in the 1950s and 1960s.\n\nIn 1973, a particular form of [[profit sharing]] scheme was introduced. When Handelsbanken meets its goals of higher [[return on equity]] than the average of the other listed Swedish banks, a profit share is paid to a foundation named Oktogonen, which keeps its fund entirely in Handelsbanken shares. Payment only takes place after retirement, which means that all employees are interested in securing the long-term profitability of the bank. Oktogonen owns around 10 per cent of Handelsbanken's shares.\n\nIn 1970, Handelsbanken installed its first six [[automated teller machine]]s (ATMs), initially as a trial.<ref name=\"SHB hist\"/>\n\nIn 1985, many aspects of the Swedish financial sector were deregulated which led to a considerable credit expansion in the following years. Handelsbanken's volume of loans doubled in three years in the end of the 1980s. Sk\u00e5nska Banken and its 76 branch offices was acquired in 1990.\n\n===1990\u2013present===\nIn 1990, Sweden entered a severe financial crisis, which was compounded by the credit expansion of the late 1980s and a [[financial bubble]] related to [[real estate]] prices. Many of the Swedish banks were hit hard by this crisis and had to be [[Swedish banking rescue|rescued by the government]], which led to some of the banks being temporarily nationalised. Handelsbanken was least affected of the major Swedish banks, and was able to expand its market share in the 1990s. In 1997, Handelsbanken bought [[Stadshypotek]], a major mortgage company, from the government.\n\nIn the 1980s Handelsbanken opened several branch offices in other countries mostly to support corporate banking activities. From 1990, several smaller Norwegian, Finnish and Danish banks were acquired to build up Handelsbanken's activities and branch networks in the other [[Nordic countries]]. In 1998, Handelsbanken's operations in Denmark, Finland and Norway were organised into regional banks, and started to operate in the same way as the regional bank organisation used by Handelsbanken in Sweden since the 1970s.\n\nIn late 1991, the bank introduced [[telephone banking]] services and on 10 December 1997 [[online banking]] followed.\n\nIn 1995, Handelsbanken acquired the vast majority of the credit and financing portfolio of the former Finnish bank [[SKOP Bank]] (<small>[[:fi:S\u00e4\u00e4st\u00f6pankkien Keskus-Osake-Pankki|fi]]</small>; which went bust in the [[Finnish banking crisis of 1990s|early-1990s Finnish banking crisis]] and the [[Early 1990s depression in Finland|recession that followed]]), as well as SKOP's holdings in the Finnish Industrialisation Fund <small>([[:fi:Teollistamisrahasto|fi:Teollistamisrahasto]])</small>. \n\nIn 1999, Handelsbanken decided to expand in the United Kingdom by organic growth. At that time the bank had three offices in the UK and opened a fourth in 2000. In 2007, the bank opened its 50th UK branch office, and in 2011 its 100th UK branch office. In 2002, the UK operations were organised as a regional bank, in the same way as the bank's Nordic operations.<ref name=\"SHB hist\"/>\n\n== Subsidiaries and branches ==\n[[File:Handelsbanken, Scott Lane, Wetherby (3rd August 2015).JPG|thumb|right|Handelsbanken's branch office in [[Wetherby]], [[England]].]]\nHome markets:\n* Sweden (more than 450 branches)\n* United Kingdom (more than 200 branches)\n* Denmark (more than 50 branches)\n* Finland (more than 30 branches)\n* Norway (more than 40 branches)\n* Netherlands (more than 25 branches)\nInternational network:\n* Germany \n* Spain\n* Greater China (Beijing, Shanghai, Taipei and Hong Kong)\n* France\n* India\n* Luxembourg\n* Malaysia\n* Poland\n* Singapore\n* United States (New York City)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n*{{official website|http://www.handelsbanken.se/en/}}\n*{{official website|http://www.handelsbanken.com/}}\n*{{official website|https://www.handelsbanken.co.uk/}}\n\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n{{OMX Stockholm 30 companies}}\n{{UK banks}}\n{{Members of Euro Banking Association}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1871]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Swedish brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Stockholm Stock Exchange]]\n", "name_user": "Ms. M E River", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handelsbanken"}
{"title_page": "Six Flags Over Texas", "text_new": "{{About|the theme park|the flags themselves|Six flags over Texas}}\n{{short description|Theme park in Arlington, Texas}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Six Flags Over Texas\n| logo = Six Flags Over Texas logo.png\n| image = File:SFOT Main Park Entrance.JPG\n| caption = The park's main entrance in 2011\n| location = [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]]\n| location2 =  [[Texas]]\n| location3 =  USA\n| coordinates = {{Coord|32|45|20.52|N|97|4|12.80|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|region:US-TX_type:landmark}}\n| homepage = {{URL|sixflags.com/overTexas}}\n| owner = Texas Flags, Ltd.<ref>[http://investors.sixflags.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=61629&p=irol-sec Sixflags.com]</ref> (51%)\n| operator = [[Six Flags]]\n| general_manager =\n| status = Operating\n| opening_date = August 5, 1961; 58 years ago\n| closing_date =\n| previous_names =\n| season = Year-round\n| area = {{convert|212|acre|mi2}} (0.86&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n| rides = 45\n| coasters = 13\n| water_rides = 3\n| slogan = ''The Thrill Capital of Texas''\n\n}}\n[[File:SFOT Main Park Entrance.JPG|250px|right|thumb|Main park entrance to Six Flags Over Texas during their 50th Anniversary]]\n'''Six Flags Over Texas''' is a 212-acre (86 ha) [[theme park]] located in [[Arlington, Texas]], east of [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] and west of [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]. It is the first amusement park in the Six Flags chain, although later acquisitions make [[Six Flags New England]] the oldest park owned and operated by the company. The park opened on August 5, 1961, following just a year of construction and an initial [[investment]] of [[United States dollar|US$]]10 million by [[real estate]] developer [[Angus G. Wynne|Angus G. Wynne, Jr]].\n\nThe park is managed by the [[Six Flags Entertainment Corp.]], which also owns 53.1% interest of the Texas Limited Partnership that owns the park. A similar arrangement exists with the partnership that owns [[Six Flags Over Georgia]].<ref name=\"Annual Report\">{{cite web|url=http://investors.sixflags.com/~/media/Files/S/SixFlags-IR/documents/annual-reports/2015-six-flags-ar.pdf|title=2015 Six Flags Entertainment Corporation Annual Report|work=SixFlags.com|accessdate=July 20, 2016}}</ref> Six Flags Over Texas Fund, Ltd, a private-equity and asset management firm headed by Dallas businessman Jack Knox, purchased the park in 1969. Over the years the various companies that managed the park, exercised options to purchase interest in the fund. Six Flags Entertainment has an option to purchase the remaining 46.9% in 2028.<ref name=\"Annual Report\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://arlingtontodayonline.com/success-accidentally|title=Success, Accidentally|publisher=Arlington Today|date=July 30, 2016|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/companies/0249485D:US-six-flags-over-texas-fund-ltd|title=Six Flags Over Texas Fund Ltd.|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> Starting in 1991, the park was managed by [[Time Warner Entertainment]]. In 1998, Time Warner sold its interests in the Six Flags parks to [[Six Flags#History of Premier Parks|Premier Parks]] of [[Oklahoma City]], which later changed its name to Six Flags Theme Parks, Inc.\n\n==History==\n===Initial planning and construction===\nFollowing a visit to [[Disneyland]] in [[Anaheim, California]], shortly after its opening, wealthy real estate developer [[Angus G. Wynne]], Jr. decided that his home state of [[Texas]] should have a local park for entertainment. Planning for such a place began in 1959, under the leadership of Wynne and the Great Southwest Corporation, along with the backing of various [[New York City]] investors. Construction on the park began in August 1960.\n\n[[File:Six Flags over Texas Original Logo.jpg|thumb|right|The original [[logo]] for Six Flags over Texas]]\n\n[[File:Six Flags over Texas (Entrance).JPG|thumb|right|The entrance of Six Flags over Texas welcomes visitors while the Oil Derrick [[observation tower]] looms in the background.]]\n\n===Origin of the name===\nThe name \"Six Flags Over Texas\" refers to [[Six flags over Texas|the flags of the six different nations that have governed Texas]]: [[Spain]], [[France]], [[Mexico]], the [[Republic of Texas]], the [[United States|United States of America]] and the [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name=wolcott>{{cite book|author=Victoria W. Wolcott|title=Race, Riots, and Roller Coasters: The Struggle Over Segregated Recreation in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJbiA_sBjzYC&pg=PA158|date=16 August 2012|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-0759-9|page=158}}</ref> Wynne originally intended to name the park \"Texas Under Six Flags.\" Various legends have attributed the name change to his wife Joann; a group called \"The Daughters of The Texas Republic\" \u2014 of which his wife may, or may not, have been a member; or his entertainment director, Charles Meeker, stating that, \"Texas isn\u2019t 'under' anything.\"<ref name=RC117>{{cite journal | last1 = Seifert | first1 = Jeffrey | year = 2011 | title = Six Flags Over Five Decades | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 32 | issue = 3 | pages = 4\u201323 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref> The original park was divided into six separate themed areas for each of the six governing entities that have ruled over Texas. Although additional themed areas have been added, the original six can still be found within the park.\n\n===Grand opening===\nSix Flags Over Texas opened its gates from July 29 to August 4, 1961, to several local corporations that Wynne had invited as part of a \"soft-test opening.\" The park held its grand opening ceremonies on Saturday, August 5, 1961. Dignitaries included the mayors of Arlington, Dallas, Fort Worth, Grand Prairie and Irving.<ref name=RC117/> Park attendance reached 8,374. Admission was $2.75 (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|2.75|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}) for adults and $2.25 (or ${{Inflation|US|2.25|1961}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}) for children (cf. admission prices of $62.99 and $47.99 for the 2013 season); parking was 50 cents (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}) (cf. $20.00 in 2013); hamburgers were 35 cents (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.35|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}), and soft drinks were 10 cents (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.10|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}).{{Inflation-fn|US}} On opening day, guests could visit the six original themed sections: [[Mexico]], [[Spain]], [[France]], The [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]], [[Texas]] and Modern (representing the USA). According to the 1961 Park Map<ref>[http://www.rcreride.com/html/sfot_Map.html \"1961 Park Map\"], rcreride.com.</ref> there were 46 \"major attractions\" listed. The park's first season, lasting only 45 days and ending on November 25, 1961, was a success with over 550,000 visitors.\n\n===1960s===\nThe 1960s were a decade of growth for Six Flags Over Texas. The park added numerous attractions, including two new sections: [[Boomtown]], named after the boomtowns that sprang up rather quickly during Texas' oil boom era and the \"Tower Section\", named after the [[Oil Derrick]] observation tower built in 1969. The park also witnessed the birth of two classic theme park attractions: [[El Aserradero]] in 1963 and the [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Runaway Mine Train]] roller coaster in 1966. Attendance reached close to 2 million visitors a year by the end of the decade. Six Flags Over Texas was one of the locations used for filming parts of the theme song for Hanna-Barbera's newest TV show [[The Banana Splits|The Banana Splits Adventure Hour]] for the fall of 1968. Sid and Marty Krofft got their debut at Six Flags Over Texas with their very own puppet show. In 1969, Six Flags Over Texas was sold by [[Angus G. Wynne]] to a new limited partnership managed by Dallas investor Jack Knox.\n\n===1970s===\nThe park's growth and expansion continued through the 1970s. It was the setting for the opening sequence in the 1971 [[Sid and Marty Krofft]] television show ''[[Lidsville]]'', in which lead character Mark ([[Butch Patrick]]) sees a magician named Merlo ([[Charles Nelson Reilly]]) perform in one of the theaters. After that Mark went to sneak backstage after his show was over, causes Merlo's hat to enlarge and falls right through it then all of sudden Mark ends up in Lidsville the land of living hats.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e5IkCfvsdYQ Lidsville Opening Title and End Credits, YouTube]</ref> The park underwent new management in 1971 with the Penn Central Railroad. The park added two new roller coasters, more rides and a new section called \"Goodtimes Square\". The park also removed many of its less popular aging attractions in this decade as well. In 1975, a new mascot, Cyrus Cosmo - the inventor - was created and led many ad campaigns. By 1978, Six Flags Over Texas had had over 30 million visitors.\n\n===1980s===\nThe 1980s were another period of change for Six Flags Over Texas. The park added three roller coasters as well as a children's section themed after [[Pac-Man]] in 1983 and later changed to [[Looney Tunes]] in 1985. Six Flags Over Texas also introduced three popular festivals in this decade. Spring Breakout, introduced in 1984, brought live bands and excitement to the park for students on Spring Break. Six Flags also introduced [[Six Flags Fright Fest|Fright Nights]] and [[Holiday in the Park]] to increase attendance and extend the season.\n\n===1990s===\nThe 1990s started off with a bang when Six Flags Over Texas introduced the [[New Texas Giant|Texas Giant]], then the world's tallest wooden roller coaster at {{convert|143|ft|m}} tall.\n\nAfter a record year, Six Flags Over Texas went into a lull with management changes and name changes, as Six Flags headed into a new direction under [[Time Warner]]. After the 1991 season, the Spee-lunker's Cave was permanently closed.\n\nIn 1992, [[Yosemite Sam and the Gold River Adventure]] opened, a [[dark ride]] by [[Sally Corporation]] featuring the [[Looney Tunes]] characters, replacing the Speek-lunker's Cave.\n\nIn 1998, Six Flags Over Texas started off the year with the addition of [[Mr. Freeze (roller coaster)|Mr. Freeze]], a LIM coaster named after [[Mr. Freeze|the supervillain]] from [[DC Comics]] that had recently been featured in the film ''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]''.\n\nIn April, Time Warner sold its remaining interest in Six Flags Theme Parks to [[Six Flags#History of Premier Parks|Premier Parks]] of [[Oklahoma City]], which later changed its name to Six Flags. As part of the sale, Six Flags received longtime licensing deals with [[Warner Bros.]] for the theme park rights to DC Comics, Warner Bros. Animation, Hanna-Barbera, and more, and the two companies retained a strong relationship.\n\nIn 1999, Six Flags Over Texas introduced [[Batman: The Ride]], an inverted roller coaster by Swiss manufacturer [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]. After debuting at [[Six Flags Great America]] in 1992 and being duplicated four times over at other Six Flags parks, Six Flags Over Texas was the last to receive the ride until the now-defunct [[Six Flags New Orleans]] in 2002. Though unlike the others, that installation of the ride was not original, but was relocated from another park.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2000, the Looney Tunes USA children's area was restructured.\n\nIn 2001, the park introduced [[Titan (Six Flags Over Texas)|Titan]], the tallest, fastest, and longest roller coaster in the park and in the state of Texas. Located in the Texas section of the park and built by [[Giovanola]] of Switzerland, it climbs {{convert|245|ft|m|1}} and features a top speed of {{convert|85|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 2002, the park kicked off the \"Best of Texas Festival\", which brought Texas history back to the park. The park also made steps toward bringing back the past, when they reopened Casa Magnetica.\n\nIn 2003, Superman: Tower of Power, a triple drop tower ride, opened in the Tower section. It was the tallest ride of its kind in the world at the time of its opening.\n\nIn 2006, the park celebrated its 45th anniversary by adding ten new attractions geared toward families. Since then, Six Flags Over Texas had placed more emphasis on families by offering a daily parade and more characters (including [[Scooby-Doo (character)|Scooby-Doo]] and the [[Justice League]]). Six Flags Over Texas also introduced Festival Latino.\n\nFor 2007 and 2008, Six Flags Over Texas was home to \"Cirque Dreams Coobrila\", a high energy cirque-acrobatic-type show housed in the Music Mill Amphitheater. On May 17, 2008, Six Flags Over Texas introduced its first roller coaster in seven years, [[Tony Hawk's Big Spin]] (renamed Pandemonium in 2011).\n\nIn 2009, debuted the \"[[Glow in the Park Parade]]\", a nighttime parade filled with thousands of lights.\n\n===2010s===\nIn early 2010, the Texas Giant roller coaster was closed to be renovated into a steel hybrid coaster, by [[Rocky Mountain Construction]] (RMC) and was reopened on April 22, 2011, as the ''New Texas Giant'' for the park's 50th anniversary.<ref>[http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/rides/TexasGiant.aspx Texas Giant Opening April 22]</ref> In late 2010, Six Flags began the process of removing licensed theming from attractions. They terminated several licenses including their licenses with [[Tony Hawk]]. ''Tony Hawk's Big Spin'' was renamed ''Pandemonium'' in the middle of the 2011 season. ''Mr. Freeze'' was closed briefly in order to turn the trains backwards. The newly named ''Mr. Freeze Reverse Blast'' reopened on May 12, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags amusement parks prepare for thematic makeovers|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-six-flags-retheme-20101122,0,3267615.story|accessdate=27 November 2010|newspaper=LA Times|date=25 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn August 2, 2012, Six Flags Over Texas announced the last chance to ride ''[[Flashback (Six Flags Over Texas)|Flashback]]'' and ''[[Texas Chute Out]]'' was September 3, 2012.<ref name=\"FlashChuteOut\">{{cite web|title=A Pair of Popular Six Flags Over Texas Rides Are Going Away|url=http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/info/news_2012FlashbackChuteOutClosing.aspx|work=Press Release|publisher=Six Flags|accessdate=August 2, 2012|author=Six Flags Over Texas|date=August 2, 2012}}</ref> On August 30, 2012, Six Flags announced the park will be adding the world's tallest [[swing ride]] at {{Convert|400|ft|m|0|adj=on}} tall, called ''[[SkyScreamer|Texas SkyScreamer]]''. ''Texas Skyscreamer'' is located in Goodtime's Square, in the place of the former Texas Chute Out. It features a Texas theme with red, white and blue colors, along with a giant star with six other flags all on top of the tower. ''Texas SkyScreamer'' opened on May 25, 2013.<ref name=\"TTS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/assets/pdf/SFOT_Fact_Sheet.pdf|title=Texas SkyScreamer|work=SixFlags.com|accessdate=August 30, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916011119/http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/assets/pdf/SFOT_Fact_Sheet.pdf|archivedate=September 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2013, Six Flags officially announced that they would expand their kids area into ''Bugs' Bunny Boomtown''. The park also added ''Wahoo Racer,'' a new water slide to the adjacent Hurricane Harbor park in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=New for 2014|url=http://content.sixflags.com/comingin2014/|date=August 29, 2013|accessdate=August 29, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901054320/http://content.sixflags.com/comingin2014/|archivedate=September 1, 2013}}</ref> In late March 2014, Six Flags Over Texas announced for a limited time in 2014 Batman: The Ride will become ''Batman: The Ride Backwards,'' as the park reversed the trains.<ref>{{cite web|title=SFOT BB|url=https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/newsroom/batman-the-ride-backwards|date=March 25, 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326080708/https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/newsroom/batman-the-ride-backwards|archivedate=March 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2014, Six Flags announced ''[[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis]]'', a dark ride themed to the Justice League for the 2015 season.\n\nOn September 3, 2015, Six Flags announced the expansion of the Gotham City section of the park for the 2016 season. The expansion included two new rides, ''Catwoman Whip'' and ''The Riddler Revenge'', and the renovation of ''Crazy Legs'' into ''Harley Quinn Spinsanity''. The new rides opened on May 28, 2016. [https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/attractions/new-2016/facts]\n\nAt the beginning of the 2016 season, Shock Wave was closed to get ready for The New Revolution. It reopened on March 10, 2016 for Season Pass Holders. It reopened to the public on March 25, 2016.\nOn September 1, 2016, Six Flags announced ''The Joker'', a 4D Free-Fly Coaster, which opened to the public in early summer 2017.\n\n==Firsts, bests, and other records==\n===Firsts and ones of a kind===\n* First [[Six Flags]] Theme Park. This is the original Six Flags Theme Park, opened on August 5, 1961\n* First Pay one Price (POP) admission<ref name=AT0811>{{cite journal | last1 = Seifert | first1 = Jeffrey | last2 = Slade | first2 = Gary | year = 2011 | title = Six Flags Over Texas Celebrates 50th Anniversary | journal = Amusement Today | volume = 15 | issue = 5 | pages = 1B\u201323B}}</ref>\n* First theme park to feature Broadway-style shows (1961)<ref name=AT0811/>\n* First Intamin Ride, the Jet Set <ref name=RC117/>\n* First [[Log flume (attraction)|Log Flume]] \u2013 [[El Aserradero]] (1963)\n* First Mine Train [[Roller Coaster]] \u2013 The [[Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Runaway Mine Train]] (1966)\n* First relaunch of the modern-day parachute ride - [[Texas Chute Out]] (1976) Removed in 2012.<ref>[http://www.guidetosfot.com/attractions/rides/texaschuteout/ Guide to Six Flags Over Texas]</ref>\n* First Freefall Ride - Texas Cliffhanger (later renamed G-Force and then Wildcatter) (1982). Removed in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahles |first1=Andrea |title=Six Flags to add Tony Hawk rollercoaster |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/news/story/245840.html |accessdate=February 21, 2019 |work=Star-Telegram.com |date=September 24, 2007 |archiveurl=http://archive.is/wg4Zu |archivedate=December 7, 2013}}</ref>\n* First [[Rocky Mountain Construction|RMC]] I-Box hybrid coaster - New Texas Giant (2011)\n\n===Records===\n[[File:SixFlagsTower-5865.jpg|thumb|100px|right|Six Flags oil derrick]]\n* Tallest [[Roller Coaster]] in [[Texas]] - Titan (245&nbsp;ft)\n* Fastest [[Roller Coaster]] in [[Texas]] - Titan (85&nbsp;mph)\n* Largest Land Based [[Oil Derrick]] - Oil Derrick (300&nbsp;ft)\n* Tallest swing ride in the world [[SkyScreamer|Texas Skyscreamer]] (400&nbsp;ft) (2013)\n\n===Awards===\n* [[New Texas Giant|Texas Giant]] named World's Best Wooden Roller Coaster in 1998 and 1999 by ''[[Amusement Today]]'''s [[Golden Ticket Awards]].\n* [[New Texas Giant]] named Best New Coaster of 2011 by ''[[Amusement Today]]'''s [[Golden Ticket Awards]].\n\n===Incidents===\n{{Main|Incidents at Six Flags parks}}\n\n==Events==\nSix Flags Over Texas hosts several seasonal events throughout the year including:\n\n[[File:Holiday in the Park (Six Flags over Texas).JPG|thumb|right|The 'Best Time of the Year' is one of the many holiday [[tradition]]s that make up the park's annual Holiday in the Park celebration.]]\n* '''Spring Break Out''' \u2013 Taking place in the month of March, the Spring Break Out event welcomes the warm Texas weather with plenty of outdoor attractions, events, games and [[concert]] [[performance]]s. The event usually takes place over a couple of weeks, allowing various local schools\u2019 differing spring break [[holiday]]s to coincide with one of the event's weeks. It has been a park tradition since 1984.\n* '''Festival Latino''' - In April, Hispanic and Latino [[Cultural heritage|heritage]] is celebrated throughout the park. The park is alive with arts, crafts, performances by bands and dancers, as well as authentic [[cuisine]] including [[fajitas]], [[sweet corn]], [[churros]] and [[tacos]]. The annual event started in 2006.\n* '''Fright Fest''' \u2013 Originally only one night in October called 'Fright Night', Fright Fest is the annual [[Halloween]] festival at Six Flags Over Texas. Fright Fest takes place throughout the month of October and features several specialized additions to the park. [[Haunted house]]s, decorated pathways, patrolling [[ghoul]]s and spooky music all contribute to the park's transformation into a giant 'scream' park.\n* '''[[Holiday in the Park]]''' \u2013 A tradition started in 1985, Holiday in the Park is now one of the park's most popular seasonal events as the park's season winds down towards the end of November and throughout December. Hundreds of thousands of [[Christmas lights (holiday decoration)|Christmas lights]] are strung around the park buildings and rides. An authentic snow hill is available for visitors to [[Toboggan|sled]] down. Festive holiday shows, arts and crafts, and delicious seasonal food also bring the holidays to Six Flags Over Texas.\n\n[[File:Sfot gotham city.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of \"[[Gotham City]]\"-themed section of the park. [[Texas State Highway 360|SH 360]] and [[Interstate 30 (Texas)|I-30]] intersect in the immediate background, showing the proximity of the park to local roadways.]]\n\n==Areas and attractions==\n* Guide to Rides & Attractions<ref>[http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/assets/pdf/SFOT_ADA.pdf Guide to Rides & Attractions]</ref>\n\n===Star Mall===\nThe Star Mall serves as the entry gate for Six Flags Over Texas. It was one of the original sections of the park when it opened in 1961. It is named for the large star-shaped fountain located in the section.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Silver Star Carousel]]'''\n|align=center|1963\n|Dentzel [[carousel]]\n|Last carousel built by William Dentzel. Originally located in Boomtown section, ride was removed for restoration in 1985 and reopened at current location in 1988.\n|\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Silver Star Carousel Stage \u2013 Located between the entrance and exit stairways to the Silver Star Carousel attraction, this multi-leveled stage showcases a variety of performances throughout the regular park operating season and during private park events as well. Although the stage is relatively small in size,{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=August 2017}} performances include dance spectacles during both Fright Fest and Holiday in the Park, school and private band recitals, and the daily Looney Tunes Party Rockin' Dance Party (March\u2013September).\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Pink Things\n* Flags Famous Funnel Cakes\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* $10 and Under\n\n'''Other guest services:'''\n* Guest services\n* Locker rental\n* Six Flags Season Pass Processing Center\n* Stroller rental\n* The [[Flash Pass]] Reservation Center\n* VIP Tours\n\n===Mexico & Spain===\nThe Mexico & Spain area consists of two sections both of which were originally part of the park in 1961. Both sections represent a flag that has flown over the state of Texas.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''El Sombrero'''\n|align=center|1965\n|[[Chance Rides]] [[Wipeout (ride)|trabant]]\n|Moved to new location in 2006.\n|\n|-\n|'''La Fiesta de las Tazas'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] [[teacups]]\n|Built in the former location of El Sombrero.\n|\n|-\n|'''Conquistador'''\n|align=center|1981\n|[[Intamin]] Bounty swinging ship\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[La Vibora]]'''\n|align=center|1986\n|[[Intamin]] Swiss Bob / [[Bobsled roller coaster]]\n|Ride was moved from [[Six Flags Magic Mountain]]. Originally named The Avalanche Bobsled.\n|[[File:SFOT Vibora 4 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[El Aserradero]]'''\n|align=center|1963\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] [[Log flume (ride)|Log flume]]\n|World's First Log Flume. Features two separate log flumes: Flume I (1963) & Flume II (1968). Flume 1 is currently Standing But Not Operating.\n|[[File:SixFlags-Log-Flume-5793.jpg|thumb|215x215px]]\n|-\n|'''El Diablo'''\n|align=center|2019\n|[[Larson International|Larson]] Giga Loop 100 Ft<ref>http://larsonintl.com/the-giga-loop-100-ft/</ref>\n|Originally called \"Lone Star Revolution,\" and planned to be placed in the tower section. The ride was recently renamed and moved to the Spain themed area.\n|[[File:El Diablo.jpg|alt=El Diablo|thumb|El Diablo]]\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Flags Funnel Cakes\n* Rancho de Pollo\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Six Flags Radio \u2013 located across from Indian Trading Village, guests can watch as specially-hired Six Flags Radio personalities\u2014referred to as DJs\u2014broadcast park-wide from inside the park's very own radio station.\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Casa de Six Flags\n* Mercado de la Plaza\n\n===Texas===\nThe Texas section of the park was another original section when the park opened in 1961. It is named after the Republic of Texas flag that once flew over the state.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Boot Scootin''''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] boot-themed Jump Around\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Chaparral Antique Cars'''\n|align=center|1962\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] antique cars\n|Entrance & Station relocated in 2011 and returned to its original entrance in 2016.\n|\n|-\n|'''Rodeo'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Huss Park Attractions|Huss]] [[Breakdance (ride)|Rodeo/Breakdance]]\n|Ride moved from [[Six Flags Great Adventure]].\n|[[File:Rodeo SFOT.jpg|alt=Rodeo|thumb|Rodeo]]\n|-\n|'''Sidewinder'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Eli Bridge]] [[Twist (ride)|Scrambler]]\n|Ride moved from [[Six Flags Astroworld]].\n|[[File:Sidewinder SFOT.jpg|alt=Sidewinder|thumb|Sidewinder]]\n|-\n|'''[[Six Flags & Texas Railroad]]'''\n|align=center|1961\n|{{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railways|narrow gauge]] train ride around the park.\n|Stations are the Texas Depot and Boomtown Depot.\n|[[File:Six Flags & Texas Railroad.jpg|alt=Six Flags & Texas Railroad|thumb|Six Flags & Texas Railroad]]\n|-\n|'''[[New Texas Giant]]'''\n|align=center|2011\n|Renovations by [[Rocky Mountain Construction]] / Hybrid roller coaster\n|It won the Golden Ticket Award for World's Best Wooden Roller Coaster of 1999. Closed for renovation in 2010. Reopened on April 22, 2011 as the world's first Rocky Mountain Construction (RMC) hybrid coaster. It won the Golden Ticket Award for Best New Coaster of 2011.\n|[[File:SFOT Giant 2 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Titan (Six Flags Over Texas)|Titan]]'''\n|align=center|2001\n|[[Giovanola]] / [[Hypercoaster]]\n|Tallest, fastest, and longest roller coaster in Texas.\n|[[File:SFOT Titan 18 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''Yosemite Sam And The Gold River Adventure'''\n|align=center|1994\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] Water [[Dark ride]]\n|Originally Opened in 1964 as Spee-Lunker's Cave Ride, name/theme changed in 1994.\u00a0It is currently [[Standing But Not Operating]].<ref>https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/attractions/yosemite-sams-gold-river-adventure</ref><ref>http://www.screamscape.com/html/six_flags_over_texas.htm</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Back Porch Stage \u2013 This venue houses live bands during certain times of the year.\n* Courthouse Stage \u2013 This small, porch-like stage comes equipped with a splash zone for use in various period gunfighting performances during the summer.\n* Crazy Horse Saloon \u2013 The Crazy Horse Saloon has provided live entertainment for over 40 years, featuring cowboys and saloon girls. This is the oldest theater in the park.\n* Lone Star Gazebo \u2013 Directly adjacent to the Lone Star Theater entrance, this space now houses Six Flags Karaoke (March \u2013 late September).\n* Lone Star Theater \u2013 This venue usually houses specialty shows.\n* Lip Synch Challenge \u2013 Its when two people challenge each other to lip synch. It was originally in the Goodtimes Square section.\n[[File:Chaparral Antique Cars attraction at Six Flags Over Texas.JPG|right|thumb|200px|A woman and boy ride on the Chaparral Antique Cars attraction.]]\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* [[Coca-Cola Freestyle]]\n* E.G. Sugarwaters\n* [[Panda Express]]\n* Bubba's Texas Giant Hot Dogs\n* Newman's Corn Dogs\n* Miss Abby's Cookies and Ice Cream Shoppe\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Indian Trading Post\n* Texas Gift Shop\n* The Ole' Woodcutter Shop\n\n[[File:Wooden roller coaster txgi.jpg|right|300x|thumb|The Texas Giant before renovations]]\n[[File:The NEW Texas Giant.jpg|thumb|The Texas Giant after renovations]]\n[[File:Observationtower sfot.jpg|thumb|right|180px|The [[Oil Derrick (Six Flags Over Texas)|Oil Derrick]] observation tower]]\n[[File:SixFlagsWaterRide-3943.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Roaring Rapids river ride (2007)]]\n[[File:SupermanTower-5954.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Superman Tower of Power]]\n\n===Old South & France===\nThe Old South & France area consists of two sections both of which were originally part of the park in 1961. Both sections represent a flag that has flown over the state of Texas. The Old South was originally called The Confederacy and featured [[American Civil War reenactment|Civil War reenactments]], including performances representing the execution of a captured [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] spy.<ref name=wolcott/>\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Runaway Mountain]]'''\n|align=center|1996\n|[[Premier Rides]] / [[Enclosed roller coaster]]\n|Indoor coaster almost completely in the dark\n|[[File:Runaway Mountain.jpg|alt=Runaway Mountain|thumb|Runaway Mountain]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Mtn. 1 Edit.jpg|thumb|link=Special:FilePath/SFOT_Mtn._1_Edit.jpg]] -->\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* David Blackburn Southern Palace Theater - The largest indoor theater at Six Flags Over Texas. This venue houses all types of musical and dance shows.\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Cold Stone Creamery (formerly [[Ben & Jerrys]])\n* JB's Smokehouse Barbeque (formerly Gator McGee's Mountain Grill)\n* Primo's Pizzeria\n* Uncle Bub's Smokehouse\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Antique Photo Emporium\n* Les De Caricatures\n* M-Porium\n\n===USA===\nThe USA area of the park opened with the park in 1961. It was originally named the Modern Section, but still represented the United States flag that has flown over Texas.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis|Justice League : Battle for Metropolis]]'''\n|align=center|2015\n|Interactive, 3-D, multi-motion base [[dark ride]]. Collaboration of [[Sally Dark Rides]], [[Alterface]], [[Oceaneering International]] and Pure Imagination Studios.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amusementtoday.com/2015/05/six-flags-over-texas-debuts-state-of-the-art-dark-ride/ |title=Six Flags Over Texas debuts state of the art dark ride |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=20 May 2015 |publisher=Amusement Today |access-date= 21 December 2015}}</ref>\n|Themed to Justice League. Debuted on May 19, 2015. Riders wear 3-D glasses and shoot at targets generated in real-time.\n|-\n|'''Aquaman: Power Wave'''\n|align=center|2020\n|[[Mack Rides]] PowerSplash coaster <ref>https://sixflags.com/overtexas/newsroom/newfor2020</ref>\n|Shuttle coaster with 3 launches, ending with a splashdown.\n|\n|}\n\n====Bugs Bunny Boomtown====\nIt is the children's area of the park. It originally opened in 1983 as [[Pac-Man]] Land. With the introduction of Looney Tunes characters to the park, it was renamed to Looney Tunes Land around 1985. In 2001, the area was renamed once again when it was expanded to include new attractions. It was renamed Bugs Bunny Boomtown for 2014.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Daffy Duck Bucket Blasters'''\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Zamperla]] Watermania\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Looney Tunes Adventure Camp'''\n|align=center|2014\n|Miracle Recreation Equipment play structure\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Marvin the Martian Space Rockets'''\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Zamperla]] Rocket Ride\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Speedy Gonzales' Truckin' Across America'''\n|align=center|1992\n|[[Zamperla]] Kiddie convoy/truck ride\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Sylvester & Tweety's State Fair-is Wheel'''\n|align=center|2001\n|[[Zamperla]] mini [[Ferris wheel]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Taz Tornado Swings'''\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Zamperla]] Lolly Swing\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Bugs Bunny Cloud Bouncer'''\n|align=center|2001\n|SBF/VISA group Happy Tower\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Wile E. Coyote's Grand Canyon Blaster]]'''\n|align=center|2001\n|[[Chance Rides]] Big Dipper / Junior coaster\n|\n|[[File:SFOT Coyote 10 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Coyote 8 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''Yosemite Sam's Texas Tea Cups'''\n|align=center|2001\n|SBF/VISA group mini [[teacups]]\n|\n|\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Bill's Lemonade\n* Granny's Grill\n* Six Flags All-American Cafe (Formerly USA Food Court)\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* ACME Rock-N-Rocket Shop (Closed at the end of 2014 to get ready for Justice League - Battle for Metropolis)\n* Cartoon Clubhouse\n* Looney Tunes Mall/Candy Corner\n* Studio 6F (Formerly Attitudes)\n\n'''Other Guest Services:'''\n* Baby Care\n* Lost Parents\n\n===Goodtimes Square===\nThe Goodtimes Square section of the park opened in 1973. Over the years, it took on a loose 1950s theme. Some of Goodtimes Square expanded to the Gotham City Section for the 2016-2017 season.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Cloud Bouncer'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] Samba balloon tower\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Judge Roy Scream]]'''\n|align=center|1980\n|Don Rosser & [[William Cobb|Bill Cobb]] / [[wooden roller coaster]]\n|Built outside main park area, along the park's entrance lake.\n|[[File:Judge Roy Scream SFOT.jpg|alt=Judge Roy Scream|thumb|Judge Roy Scream]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Scream 2 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''[[SkyScreamer|Texas SkyScreamer]]'''\n|align=center|2013\n|[[Funtime (manufacturer)|Funtime]] [[Swings (ride)|Star Flyer]]\n|Second Tallest Star Flyer in the world, standing 400&nbsp;ft.<ref name=\"TTS\"/>\n|[[File:Texas SkyScreamer SFOT.jpg|alt=Texas SkyScreamer|thumb|Texas SkyScreamer]]\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Majestic Theater - Originally the Krofft Puppet Circus & Goodtimes Theater, this venue houses all types of musical, dance and specialty shows.\n\n===Gotham City===\nGotham City opened in 1999 and is themed to the [[DC Comics]] [[Batman]] universe.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Batman: The Ride]]'''\n|align=center|1999\n|[[Bolliger & Mabillard]] / [[Inverted roller coaster]]\n|Is the only inverted coaster in the park. Trains were reversed for the 2014 season.\n|[[File:SFOT Batman 31 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Batman 3 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''Batwing'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] Telecombat\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Catwoman Whip'''\n|align=center|2016\n|[[Zamperla]] Endeavor\n|\n|[[File:Catwoman Whip.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''Harley Quinn Spinsanity'''\n|align=center|2018\n|ABC Rides Tourbillon\n|\n|[[File:HQS2.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Mr. Freeze (roller coaster)|Mr. Freeze: Reverse Blast]]''' <ref>[http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/rides/MrFreezeReverseBlast.aspx \"Mr.Freeze Reverse Blast\"], Six Flags Over Texas website.</ref>\n|align=center|1998\n|[[Premier Rides]] [[linear motor|LIM]] / [[Launched roller coaster]]\n|Originally intended to open for the 1997 season, but problems with the LIM Launch system delayed opening until 1998. Trains were reversed and ride renamed to Mr. Freeze: Reverse Blast in 2012.\n|[[File:Mr Freeze SFOT.jpg|alt=Mr Freeze|thumb|Mr Freeze]]\n|-\n| '''[[The Joker (S&S Worldwide)|The Joker]]'''\n|align=center|2017\n|[[S&S Worldwide]] 4D Free Spin\n|\n|[[File:SFOT Joker 5 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Joker 13 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''[[The Riddler Revenge]]'''\n|align=center|2016\n|[[Zamperla]] Giant Discovery ride.\n|\n|[[File:Riddler's Revenge.jpg|thumb]]\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Gotham Snacks\n* [[Johnny Rockets]]\n[[File:Inverted coaster btr.jpg|thumb|right|[[Batman: The Ride]] at Six Flags Over Texas]]\n\n===Boomtown===\nThe Boomtown section opened in 1963. It is based on the Texas boomtowns that sprung up in Texas during the oil boom era.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Mini Mine Train]]'''\n|align=center|1969\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] / [[Mine train roller coaster]]\n|Located next to the bigger Runaway Mine Train and Mr. Freeze. Track modified slightly in 1997 when Mr. Freeze was built next to/over parts of the track.\n|[[File:SFOT Mini 3 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Pandemonium (roller coaster)|Pandemonium]]''' <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-six-flags-retheme-20101122,0,3267615.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Brady | last=MacDonald | title=Six Flags amusement parks prepare for thematic makeovers | date=November 25, 2010}}</ref>\n|align=center|2008\n|Gerstlauer / [[Spinning roller coaster]]\n|Originally named \"Tony Hawk's Big Spin\".\n|[[File:Pandemonium SFOT.jpg|alt=Pandemonium|thumb|Pandemonium]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Big Spin 11 Edit.jpg|thumb|link=Special:FilePath/SFOT_Big_Spin_11_Edit.jpg]] -->\n|-\n|'''[[Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Runaway Mine Train]]'''\n|align=center|1966\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]] / [[Mine train roller coaster]]\n|First [[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] mine train coaster.\n|[[File:SFOT Mine 7 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Six Flags & Texas Railroad]]'''\n|align=center|1961\n|{{RailGauge|3ft}} narrow gauge train ride around the park.\n|Stations are the Texas Depot and Boomtown Depot.\n|[[File:SFOT Train.jpg|alt=SFOT Train|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''The Gunslinger'''\n|align=center|1983\n|[[Chance Rides]] [[Yo-Yo (ride)|Yo-Yo]] swings ride\n|Ride was named Texas Tornado until 2007.\n|\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Dry Hole Charlie's\n* Dusty Dan's Waterin' Hole\n* Macho Nacho (Formally Goldminer's Diner)\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Caricatures\n\n[[File:SixFlagsTrain-4027.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Six Flags & Texas Railroad (2007)]]\n[[File:SixFlagsKiddieSwing-4069.jpg|thumb|right|180px|The Gunslinger [[swing ride]] (2007)]]\n\n===Tower===\nThe Tower Section opened in 1969 and is named after the Oil Derrick tower location in the section.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Caddo Lake Barge'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] Rockin\u2019 Tug\n|\n|[[File:Caddo Lake Barge.jpg|alt=Caddo Lake Barge|thumb|Caddo Lake Barge]]\n|-\n|'''Dive Bomber Alley'''\n|align=center|1996\n|[[Skycoaster]]\n|Requires additional charge.\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Oil Derrick (Six Flags Over Texas)|Oil Derrick]]'''\n|align=center|1969\n|[[Intamin]] [[observation tower]]\n|Largest land-based [[oil derrick]] in the world standing 300&nbsp;ft tall.\n|[[File:Oil Derrick.jpg|alt=Oil Derrick|thumb|Oil Derrick]]\n|-\n|'''[[Roaring Rapids]]'''\n|align=center|1983\n|[[Intamin]] [[river rapids ride]]\n|Replaced Skull Island and LaSalle's Riverboat Adventure.\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Shock Wave (Six Flags Over Texas)|Shock Wave]]'''\n|align=center|1978\n|Schwarzkopf / Looping roller coaster\n|Steel coaster with two back-to-back vertical loops.\n|[[File:SFOT Shockwave 9 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Shockwave 5 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''Six Flags Speedway Go Karts'''\n|align=center|1999\n|J & J Amusements [[kart racing|go karts]]\n|Requires additional charge.\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Superman Tower Of Power]]'''\n|align=center|2003\n|3 [[S&S Worldwide]] [[Turbo Drop|Combo Towers]]\n|Tallest S&S Combo Tower in the world standing 325&nbsp;ft tall.\n|[[File:Superman Tower of Power SFOT.jpg|alt=Superman Tower of Power|thumb|Superman Tower of Power]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Superman Tower of Power (SFOT).jpg|thumb]] -->\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Music Mill Amphitheater - The park's large outdoor amphitheater. This venue houses concerts and other live entertainment.\n* Texas Arena - This is the park's stunt show theater. In 2008, the Thursday Night Starburst Concert Series performed here.\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Oliver's Tavern\n* Lone Star Twister Pretzels\n* Newman's Cafe\n* Flags Funnel Cakes (Formally Red River Dogs & Fries changed during Fright Fest 2014)\n\n==Former attractions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=126|Ride Name\n!width=50|Opened\n!width=50|Closed\n!Manufacturer\n!Ride Model/Type\n!Location\n!Notes\n\n!Photo\n\n|-\n|'''Aquaman Splashdown'''\n|align=center|1987\n|align=center|2019\n|[[Hopkins Rides]]\n|[[Shoot-the-Chutes]]\n|USA\n|Ride was named Splash Water Falls until 2007. Will be replaced by Aquaman Power Wave.\n|[[File:20190330 125959 Edit.jpg|alt=Aquaman Splashdown|thumb|Aquaman Splashdown]]\n|-\n|'''Big Bend'''\n|align=center|1971\n|align=center|1979\n|[[Anton Schwarzkopf|Schwarzkopf]]\n|Speed Racer\n|USA\n|Ride relocated to [[Six Flags St. Louis]], but was never re-assembled and was later scrapped.\n|\n|-\n|'''Bugs Bunny's Spirit of St. Louie'''\n|align=center|1976\n|align=center|2013\n|[[Zamperla]]\n|Mini airplane ride\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Caddo War Canoes'''\n|align=center|1962\n|align=center|1983\n|\n|[[Canoe|Canoe Ride]]\n|Boomtown\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Cinesphere Chevy Show'''\n|align=center|1969\n|align=center|1984\n|\n|[[70 mm film#Omnivision Cinema 180|Cinema 180]]\n|Old South\n|Current Lone Star Theater\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Daffy Duck's Capitol Tours'''\n|align=center|2001\n|align=center|2013\n|SBF/VISA group\n|Kiddie crazy bus ride\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Ferrocarril Fiesta Train'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1978\n|\n|[[Miniature Railway|Train Ride]]\n|Mexico\n|Updated in 1968\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Flashback'''\n|align=center|1989\n|align=center|2012\n|[[Vekoma]]\n|[[Boomerang (roller coaster)|Boomerang]]\n|Goodtimes Square\n|It was closed on September 3, 2012. Ride relocated to [[Six Flags St. Louis]], re-opened in 2013 as Boomerang\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Great Six Flags Air Racer'''\n|align=center|1984\n|align=center|1999\n|[[Intamin AG]]\n|Air Racer\n|Tower\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Harley Quinn Spinsanity'''\n|align=center|2006\n|align=center|2018\n|[[HUSS Park Attractions|Huss]]\n|Troika\n|Goodtimes Square\n|Removed before the start of the 2018 season. The ride was originally named Crazy Legs from 2006-2016. Ride relocated from [[Six Flags Astroworld]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''La Cucaracha'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1964\n|[[Allan Herschell Company|Allan Herschell]]\n|[[Wild Mouse roller coaster|Wild Mouse]]\n|Mexico\n|Originally named Sidewinder and was located in the USA section in 1961. Name changed and moved to Mexico section in 1962.\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Las Cocheses Cabras Goat Cart'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1963\n|\n|\n|Mexico\n|Goat powered cart ride\n\n|\n|-\n|'''LaSalle's Riverboat Expedition'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1982\n|\n|[[Water ride|Guided Old Mill]]\n|France\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Little Dixie Carousel'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1974\n|\n|[[Carousel|Animal Powered Carousel]]\n|Old South\n|Also known as Flying Jenny\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Los Conquistadores Mule Pack Ride Coronado Trek'''<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rcreride.com/html/sfot_Map.html |title= 1961 Map of Six Flags Over Texas  |publisher= American Coaster Enthusiasts |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1962\n|\n|\n|Spain\n|Although titled \"mule pack ride,\" guests actually rode burros and were led by a host dressed as conquistador, riding a horse.<ref name=RC117/>\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Michigan J. Frog's Tinsel Town Revue'''\n|align=center|1985\n|align=center|2013\n|[[Zamperla]]\n|Mini [[swinger (ride)|swinger ride]]\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Overland Butterfield Stagecoach'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1967\n|\n|[[Stagecoach]]\n|Old South\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Rotoriculous'''\n|align=center|1975\n|align=center|1988\n|[[Reverchon Industries|Reverchon]]\n|Himalaya\n|Goodtimes Square\n|Ride was enclosed\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Route 66 Bumper Cars'''\n|align=center|2001\n|align=center|2013\n|SBF/VISA group\n|Mini [[bumper cars]]\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Skull Island'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1982\n|\n|[[Playground]]\n|Skull Island\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Sky Hook'''\n|align=center|1963\n|align=center|1968\n|\n|Sky Crane\n|Boomtown\n|An observation ride adapted from a cargo crane by Von Roll of Switzerland.<ref name=RC117/> Ride relocated to [[Six Flags Over Georgia]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Spee-Lunker's Cave'''\n|align=center|1964\n|align=center|1991\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n|[[Dark ride|Floating Dark Ride]]\n|Texas\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Spindletop'''\n|align=center|1967\n|align=center|1989\n|[[Chance Rides]]\n|[[Rotor (ride)|Rotor]]\n|Goodtimes Square/Texas\n|Relocated to [[Frontier City]] where it's currently operating and renamed Terrible Twister and then Tumbleweed in 2014.\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Spinnaker'''\n|align=center|1977\n|align=center|1995\n|[[Anton Schwarzkopf|Schwarzkopf GmbH]]\n|[[Enterprise (ride)|Enterprise]]\n|Tower\n|Relocated to [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Texas Chute Out]]'''\n|align=center|1976\n|align=center|2012\n|[[Intamin AG]]\n|Parachute Tower\n|Goodtimes Square\n|Demolished on October 10, 2012. Replaced by [[Texas SkyScreamer|SkyScreamer]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Tower Slide'''\n|align=center|1969\n|align=center|1976\n|\n|[[Fun Slide]]\n|Tower Section\n|\n|\n|-\n<ref>guidetosfot.com/rides/oilderrick/</ref>\n|'''Virtual Quest'''\n|align=center|2001\n|align=center|2005\n|\n|[[Virtual reality]]\n|Goodtimes Square\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''ACME Rock-n-Rocket'''\n|align=center|2006\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Intamin AG]]\n|[[Looping Starship]]\n|USA\n|Closed on August 24, 2014. Replaced by Justice League:Battle for Metropolis\n|\n|-\n|}\n* '''Turbo Bungy''' - [[bungee cord|bungee]] [[trampoline]]\n* '''Helicopter Rides''' - [[helicopter]] tours above the park\n* '''Astro-Lift''' - A [[Von Roll Holding|Von Roll]] [[Von Roll Holding#VonRoll type 101s ever built|type 101 aerial ropeway]] across the park\n* '''Humble's Happy Motoring Freeway Track I & II''' - [[Arrow Dynamics]] guide-limited auto ride\n* '''Jet Set''' - individual controlled mini jets. Intamin's very first ride.<ref name=RC117/>\n* '''Missile Chaser''' - classic [[Twist (ride)|scrambler]] that was moved to [[Six Flags Magic Mountain]]\n* '''Petting Zoo''' - [[petting zoo]]\n* '''Wildcatter''' ([[Intamin]] [[freefall (ride)|1st-Generation Intamin Freefall]]) - originally called Texas Cliffhanger; opened in 1982; located in USA \"Boomtown\" section. The ride was demolished in October 2007.\n* '''[[SpongeBob SquarePants 4-D|SpongeBob SquarePants: The Ride]]''' ([[motion simulator]] theater) - opened in 2004; located in USA section. Removed after 2007 season.\n* '''Bumper Cars''' (Soli [[bumper cars]]) - opened in 1973; located in Goodtimes Square section. Closed in August 2007 for Fright Fest and remained closed after the 2007 season.\n* '''[[Crazy Legs (amusement ride)|Crazy Legs]]''' ([[Eyerly Aircraft]] Monster) - opened in 1973; closed after the 1980 season.\n* '''Porky Pig Magic Wheel''' - was a typical [[Eli Bridge|Eli Bridge Company]] model [[Ferris wheel]] located in Looney Tunes USA where the current \"Fair-is Wheel\" is located.\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn August 2017, in response to the controversial [[Unite the Right rally]] that was held in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], the park replaced its six flags (which had included the [[Flags of the Confederate States of America#First flag: the \"Stars and Bars\" (1861\u20131863)|original Confederate flag]]) with six American flags. A representative of the park told [[KXAS-TV]], \"We always choose to focus on celebrating the things that unite us versus those that divide us. As such, we have changed the flag displays in our park to feature American flags.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2017/08/18/six-flags-confederate-flags/|title=Six Flags Pulls Down Confederate Flags|last1=Morris|first1=David Z.|date=August 18, 2017|work=Fortune|access-date=August 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2017/08/18/six-flags-over-texas-removes-confederate-flag-reversing-earlier-decision.html|title=Six Flags Over Texas removes Confederate flag, reversing earlier decision &#124; Fox News|date=August 18, 2017|website=FoxNews.com|access-date=August 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Trains}}\n* [[Six Flags Hurricane Harbor]]\n* [[List of amusement parks in the Americas]]\n* [[Incidents at Six Flags parks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n* Jordan, Scott L. [https://archive.is/20130103214903/http://www.mouseplanet.com/scott/072400.htm MousePlanet - This Old Park]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n* McCown, Davis. [http://parktimes.com ParkTimes]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n* Rogers, Joel A. [http://www.coastergallery.com/2001T/SFOT.html CoasterGallery.com]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040922014822/http://www.sixflags.com/media_info.asp Six Flags - Media Info]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas Six Flags Over Texas official website]\n* {{RCDB|4531}}\n\n{{Six Flags}}\n{{Six Flags Over Texas}}\n{{Arlington, Texas}}\n\n[[Category:Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Texas]]\n[[Category:Six Flags amusement parks|Over Texas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Tarrant County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in Texas]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Six Flags Over Texas| ]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Tarrant County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1961]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the theme park|the flags themselves|Six flags over Texas}}\n{{short description|Theme park in Arlington, Texas}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Six Flags Over Texas\n| logo = Six Flags Over Texas logo.png\n| image = File:SFOT Main Park Entrance.JPG\n| caption = The park's main entrance in 2011\n| location = [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]]\n| location2 =  [[Texas]]\n| location3 =  USA\n| coordinates = {{Coord|32|45|20.52|N|97|4|12.80|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|region:US-TX_type:landmark}}\n| homepage = {{URL|sixflags.com/overTexas}}\n| owner = Texas Flags, Ltd.<ref>[http://investors.sixflags.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=61629&p=irol-sec Sixflags.com]</ref> (51%)\n| operator = [[Six Flags]]\n| general_manager =\n| status = Temporarily Closed due to [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]\n| opening_date = August 5, 1961; 58 years ago\n| closing_date =\n| previous_names =\n| season = Year-round\n| area = {{convert|212|acre|mi2}} (0.86&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n| rides = 45\n| coasters = 13\n| water_rides = 3\n| slogan = ''The Thrill Capital of Texas''\n\n}}\n[[File:SFOT Main Park Entrance.JPG|250px|right|thumb|Main park entrance to Six Flags Over Texas during their 50th Anniversary]]\n'''Six Flags Over Texas''' is a 212-acre (86 ha) [[theme park]] located in [[Arlington, Texas]], east of [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] and west of [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]. It is the first amusement park in the Six Flags chain, although later acquisitions make [[Six Flags New England]] the oldest park owned and operated by the company. The park opened on August 5, 1961, following just a year of construction and an initial [[investment]] of [[United States dollar|US$]]10 million by [[real estate]] developer [[Angus G. Wynne|Angus G. Wynne, Jr]].\n\nThe park is managed by the [[Six Flags Entertainment Corp.]], which also owns 53.1% interest of the Texas Limited Partnership that owns the park. A similar arrangement exists with the partnership that owns [[Six Flags Over Georgia]].<ref name=\"Annual Report\">{{cite web|url=http://investors.sixflags.com/~/media/Files/S/SixFlags-IR/documents/annual-reports/2015-six-flags-ar.pdf|title=2015 Six Flags Entertainment Corporation Annual Report|work=SixFlags.com|accessdate=July 20, 2016}}</ref> Six Flags Over Texas Fund, Ltd, a private-equity and asset management firm headed by Dallas businessman Jack Knox, purchased the park in 1969. Over the years the various companies that managed the park, exercised options to purchase interest in the fund. Six Flags Entertainment has an option to purchase the remaining 46.9% in 2028.<ref name=\"Annual Report\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://arlingtontodayonline.com/success-accidentally|title=Success, Accidentally|publisher=Arlington Today|date=July 30, 2016|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/companies/0249485D:US-six-flags-over-texas-fund-ltd|title=Six Flags Over Texas Fund Ltd.|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> Starting in 1991, the park was managed by [[Time Warner Entertainment]]. In 1998, Time Warner sold its interests in the Six Flags parks to [[Six Flags#History of Premier Parks|Premier Parks]] of [[Oklahoma City]], which later changed its name to Six Flags Theme Parks, Inc.\n\n==History==\n===Initial planning and construction===\nFollowing a visit to [[Disneyland]] in [[Anaheim, California]], shortly after its opening, wealthy real estate developer [[Angus G. Wynne]], Jr. decided that his home state of [[Texas]] should have a local park for entertainment. Planning for such a place began in 1959, under the leadership of Wynne and the Great Southwest Corporation, along with the backing of various [[New York City]] investors. Construction on the park began in August 1960.\n\n[[File:Six Flags over Texas Original Logo.jpg|thumb|right|The original [[logo]] for Six Flags over Texas]]\n\n[[File:Six Flags over Texas (Entrance).JPG|thumb|right|The entrance of Six Flags over Texas welcomes visitors while the Oil Derrick [[observation tower]] looms in the background.]]\n\n===Origin of the name===\nThe name \"Six Flags Over Texas\" refers to [[Six flags over Texas|the flags of the six different nations that have governed Texas]]: [[Spain]], [[France]], [[Mexico]], the [[Republic of Texas]], the [[United States|United States of America]] and the [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name=wolcott>{{cite book|author=Victoria W. Wolcott|title=Race, Riots, and Roller Coasters: The Struggle Over Segregated Recreation in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJbiA_sBjzYC&pg=PA158|date=16 August 2012|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-0759-9|page=158}}</ref> Wynne originally intended to name the park \"Texas Under Six Flags.\" Various legends have attributed the name change to his wife Joann; a group called \"The Daughters of The Texas Republic\" \u2014 of which his wife may, or may not, have been a member; or his entertainment director, Charles Meeker, stating that, \"Texas isn\u2019t 'under' anything.\"<ref name=RC117>{{cite journal | last1 = Seifert | first1 = Jeffrey | year = 2011 | title = Six Flags Over Five Decades | journal = RollerCoaster! Magazine | volume = 32 | issue = 3 | pages = 4\u201323 | issn = 0896-7261}}</ref> The original park was divided into six separate themed areas for each of the six governing entities that have ruled over Texas. Although additional themed areas have been added, the original six can still be found within the park.\n\n===Grand opening===\nSix Flags Over Texas opened its gates from July 29 to August 4, 1961, to several local corporations that Wynne had invited as part of a \"soft-test opening.\" The park held its grand opening ceremonies on Saturday, August 5, 1961. Dignitaries included the mayors of Arlington, Dallas, Fort Worth, Grand Prairie and Irving.<ref name=RC117/> Park attendance reached 8,374. Admission was $2.75 (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|2.75|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}) for adults and $2.25 (or ${{Inflation|US|2.25|1961}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}) for children (cf. admission prices of $62.99 and $47.99 for the 2013 season); parking was 50 cents (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}) (cf. $20.00 in 2013); hamburgers were 35 cents (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.35|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}), and soft drinks were 10 cents (or ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.10|1961}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}).{{Inflation-fn|US}} On opening day, guests could visit the six original themed sections: [[Mexico]], [[Spain]], [[France]], The [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]], [[Texas]] and Modern (representing the USA). According to the 1961 Park Map<ref>[http://www.rcreride.com/html/sfot_Map.html \"1961 Park Map\"], rcreride.com.</ref> there were 46 \"major attractions\" listed. The park's first season, lasting only 45 days and ending on November 25, 1961, was a success with over 550,000 visitors.\n\n===1960s===\nThe 1960s were a decade of growth for Six Flags Over Texas. The park added numerous attractions, including two new sections: [[Boomtown]], named after the boomtowns that sprang up rather quickly during Texas' oil boom era and the \"Tower Section\", named after the [[Oil Derrick]] observation tower built in 1969. The park also witnessed the birth of two classic theme park attractions: [[El Aserradero]] in 1963 and the [[Runaway Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Runaway Mine Train]] roller coaster in 1966. Attendance reached close to 2 million visitors a year by the end of the decade. Six Flags Over Texas was one of the locations used for filming parts of the theme song for Hanna-Barbera's newest TV show [[The Banana Splits|The Banana Splits Adventure Hour]] for the fall of 1968. Sid and Marty Krofft got their debut at Six Flags Over Texas with their very own puppet show. In 1969, Six Flags Over Texas was sold by [[Angus G. Wynne]] to a new limited partnership managed by Dallas investor Jack Knox.\n\n===1970s===\nThe park's growth and expansion continued through the 1970s. It was the setting for the opening sequence in the 1971 [[Sid and Marty Krofft]] television show ''[[Lidsville]]'', in which lead character Mark ([[Butch Patrick]]) sees a magician named Merlo ([[Charles Nelson Reilly]]) perform in one of the theaters. After that Mark went to sneak backstage after his show was over, causes Merlo's hat to enlarge and falls right through it then all of sudden Mark ends up in Lidsville the land of living hats.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e5IkCfvsdYQ Lidsville Opening Title and End Credits, YouTube]</ref> The park underwent new management in 1971 with the Penn Central Railroad. The park added two new roller coasters, more rides and a new section called \"Goodtimes Square\". The park also removed many of its less popular aging attractions in this decade as well. In 1975, a new mascot, Cyrus Cosmo - the inventor - was created and led many ad campaigns. By 1978, Six Flags Over Texas had had over 30 million visitors.\n\n===1980s===\nThe 1980s were another period of change for Six Flags Over Texas. The park added three roller coasters as well as a children's section themed after [[Pac-Man]] in 1983 and later changed to [[Looney Tunes]] in 1985. Six Flags Over Texas also introduced three popular festivals in this decade. Spring Breakout, introduced in 1984, brought live bands and excitement to the park for students on Spring Break. Six Flags also introduced [[Six Flags Fright Fest|Fright Nights]] and [[Holiday in the Park]] to increase attendance and extend the season.\n\n===1990s===\nThe 1990s started off with a bang when Six Flags Over Texas introduced the [[New Texas Giant|Texas Giant]], then the world's tallest wooden roller coaster at {{convert|143|ft|m}} tall.\n\nAfter a record year, Six Flags Over Texas went into a lull with management changes and name changes, as Six Flags headed into a new direction under [[Time Warner]]. After the 1991 season, the Spee-lunker's Cave was permanently closed.\n\nIn 1992, [[Yosemite Sam and the Gold River Adventure]] opened, a [[dark ride]] by [[Sally Corporation]] featuring the [[Looney Tunes]] characters, replacing the Speek-lunker's Cave.\n\nIn 1998, Six Flags Over Texas started off the year with the addition of [[Mr. Freeze (roller coaster)|Mr. Freeze]], a LIM coaster named after [[Mr. Freeze|the supervillain]] from [[DC Comics]] that had recently been featured in the film ''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]''.\n\nIn April, Time Warner sold its remaining interest in Six Flags Theme Parks to [[Six Flags#History of Premier Parks|Premier Parks]] of [[Oklahoma City]], which later changed its name to Six Flags. As part of the sale, Six Flags received longtime licensing deals with [[Warner Bros.]] for the theme park rights to DC Comics, Warner Bros. Animation, Hanna-Barbera, and more, and the two companies retained a strong relationship.\n\nIn 1999, Six Flags Over Texas introduced [[Batman: The Ride]], an inverted roller coaster by Swiss manufacturer [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]. After debuting at [[Six Flags Great America]] in 1992 and being duplicated four times over at other Six Flags parks, Six Flags Over Texas was the last to receive the ride until the now-defunct [[Six Flags New Orleans]] in 2002. Though unlike the others, that installation of the ride was not original, but was relocated from another park.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2000, the Looney Tunes USA children's area was restructured.\n\nIn 2001, the park introduced [[Titan (Six Flags Over Texas)|Titan]], the tallest, fastest, and longest roller coaster in the park and in the state of Texas. Located in the Texas section of the park and built by [[Giovanola]] of Switzerland, it climbs {{convert|245|ft|m|1}} and features a top speed of {{convert|85|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 2002, the park kicked off the \"Best of Texas Festival\", which brought Texas history back to the park. The park also made steps toward bringing back the past, when they reopened Casa Magnetica.\n\nIn 2003, Superman: Tower of Power, a triple drop tower ride, opened in the Tower section. It was the tallest ride of its kind in the world at the time of its opening.\n\nIn 2006, the park celebrated its 45th anniversary by adding ten new attractions geared toward families. Since then, Six Flags Over Texas had placed more emphasis on families by offering a daily parade and more characters (including [[Scooby-Doo (character)|Scooby-Doo]] and the [[Justice League]]). Six Flags Over Texas also introduced Festival Latino.\n\nFor 2007 and 2008, Six Flags Over Texas was home to \"Cirque Dreams Coobrila\", a high energy cirque-acrobatic-type show housed in the Music Mill Amphitheater. On May 17, 2008, Six Flags Over Texas introduced its first roller coaster in seven years, [[Tony Hawk's Big Spin]] (renamed Pandemonium in 2011).\n\nIn 2009, debuted the \"[[Glow in the Park Parade]]\", a nighttime parade filled with thousands of lights.\n\n===2010s===\nIn early 2010, the Texas Giant roller coaster was closed to be renovated into a steel hybrid coaster, by [[Rocky Mountain Construction]] (RMC) and was reopened on April 22, 2011, as the ''New Texas Giant'' for the park's 50th anniversary.<ref>[http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/rides/TexasGiant.aspx Texas Giant Opening April 22]</ref> In late 2010, Six Flags began the process of removing licensed theming from attractions. They terminated several licenses including their licenses with [[Tony Hawk]]. ''Tony Hawk's Big Spin'' was renamed ''Pandemonium'' in the middle of the 2011 season. ''Mr. Freeze'' was closed briefly in order to turn the trains backwards. The newly named ''Mr. Freeze Reverse Blast'' reopened on May 12, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags amusement parks prepare for thematic makeovers|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-six-flags-retheme-20101122,0,3267615.story|accessdate=27 November 2010|newspaper=LA Times|date=25 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn August 2, 2012, Six Flags Over Texas announced the last chance to ride ''[[Flashback (Six Flags Over Texas)|Flashback]]'' and ''[[Texas Chute Out]]'' was September 3, 2012.<ref name=\"FlashChuteOut\">{{cite web|title=A Pair of Popular Six Flags Over Texas Rides Are Going Away|url=http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/info/news_2012FlashbackChuteOutClosing.aspx|work=Press Release|publisher=Six Flags|accessdate=August 2, 2012|author=Six Flags Over Texas|date=August 2, 2012}}</ref> On August 30, 2012, Six Flags announced the park will be adding the world's tallest [[swing ride]] at {{Convert|400|ft|m|0|adj=on}} tall, called ''[[SkyScreamer|Texas SkyScreamer]]''. ''Texas Skyscreamer'' is located in Goodtime's Square, in the place of the former Texas Chute Out. It features a Texas theme with red, white and blue colors, along with a giant star with six other flags all on top of the tower. ''Texas SkyScreamer'' opened on May 25, 2013.<ref name=\"TTS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/assets/pdf/SFOT_Fact_Sheet.pdf|title=Texas SkyScreamer|work=SixFlags.com|accessdate=August 30, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916011119/http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/assets/pdf/SFOT_Fact_Sheet.pdf|archivedate=September 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2013, Six Flags officially announced that they would expand their kids area into ''Bugs' Bunny Boomtown''. The park also added ''Wahoo Racer,'' a new water slide to the adjacent Hurricane Harbor park in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=New for 2014|url=http://content.sixflags.com/comingin2014/|date=August 29, 2013|accessdate=August 29, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901054320/http://content.sixflags.com/comingin2014/|archivedate=September 1, 2013}}</ref> In late March 2014, Six Flags Over Texas announced for a limited time in 2014 Batman: The Ride will become ''Batman: The Ride Backwards,'' as the park reversed the trains.<ref>{{cite web|title=SFOT BB|url=https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/newsroom/batman-the-ride-backwards|date=March 25, 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326080708/https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/newsroom/batman-the-ride-backwards|archivedate=March 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2014, Six Flags announced ''[[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis]]'', a dark ride themed to the Justice League for the 2015 season.\n\nOn September 3, 2015, Six Flags announced the expansion of the Gotham City section of the park for the 2016 season. The expansion included two new rides, ''Catwoman Whip'' and ''The Riddler Revenge'', and the renovation of ''Crazy Legs'' into ''Harley Quinn Spinsanity''. The new rides opened on May 28, 2016. [https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/attractions/new-2016/facts]\n\nAt the beginning of the 2016 season, Shock Wave was closed to get ready for The New Revolution. It reopened on March 10, 2016 for Season Pass Holders. It reopened to the public on March 25, 2016.\nOn September 1, 2016, Six Flags announced ''The Joker'', a 4D Free-Fly Coaster, which opened to the public in early summer 2017.\n\n==Firsts, bests, and other records==\n===Firsts and ones of a kind===\n* First [[Six Flags]] Theme Park. This is the original Six Flags Theme Park, opened on August 5, 1961\n* First Pay one Price (POP) admission<ref name=AT0811>{{cite journal | last1 = Seifert | first1 = Jeffrey | last2 = Slade | first2 = Gary | year = 2011 | title = Six Flags Over Texas Celebrates 50th Anniversary | journal = Amusement Today | volume = 15 | issue = 5 | pages = 1B\u201323B}}</ref>\n* First theme park to feature Broadway-style shows (1961)<ref name=AT0811/>\n* First Intamin Ride, the Jet Set <ref name=RC117/>\n* First [[Log flume (attraction)|Log Flume]] \u2013 [[El Aserradero]] (1963)\n* First Mine Train [[Roller Coaster]] \u2013 The [[Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Runaway Mine Train]] (1966)\n* First relaunch of the modern-day parachute ride - [[Texas Chute Out]] (1976) Removed in 2012.<ref>[http://www.guidetosfot.com/attractions/rides/texaschuteout/ Guide to Six Flags Over Texas]</ref>\n* First Freefall Ride - Texas Cliffhanger (later renamed G-Force and then Wildcatter) (1982). Removed in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahles |first1=Andrea |title=Six Flags to add Tony Hawk rollercoaster |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/news/story/245840.html |accessdate=February 21, 2019 |work=Star-Telegram.com |date=September 24, 2007 |archiveurl=http://archive.is/wg4Zu |archivedate=December 7, 2013}}</ref>\n* First [[Rocky Mountain Construction|RMC]] I-Box hybrid coaster - New Texas Giant (2011)\n\n===Records===\n[[File:SixFlagsTower-5865.jpg|thumb|100px|right|Six Flags oil derrick]]\n* Tallest [[Roller Coaster]] in [[Texas]] - Titan (245&nbsp;ft)\n* Fastest [[Roller Coaster]] in [[Texas]] - Titan (85&nbsp;mph)\n* Largest Land Based [[Oil Derrick]] - Oil Derrick (300&nbsp;ft)\n* Tallest swing ride in the world [[SkyScreamer|Texas Skyscreamer]] (400&nbsp;ft) (2013)\n\n===Awards===\n* [[New Texas Giant|Texas Giant]] named World's Best Wooden Roller Coaster in 1998 and 1999 by ''[[Amusement Today]]'''s [[Golden Ticket Awards]].\n* [[New Texas Giant]] named Best New Coaster of 2011 by ''[[Amusement Today]]'''s [[Golden Ticket Awards]].\n\n===Incidents===\n{{Main|Incidents at Six Flags parks}}\n\n==Events==\nSix Flags Over Texas hosts several seasonal events throughout the year including:\n\n[[File:Holiday in the Park (Six Flags over Texas).JPG|thumb|right|The 'Best Time of the Year' is one of the many holiday [[tradition]]s that make up the park's annual Holiday in the Park celebration.]]\n* '''Spring Break Out''' \u2013 Taking place in the month of March, the Spring Break Out event welcomes the warm Texas weather with plenty of outdoor attractions, events, games and [[concert]] [[performance]]s. The event usually takes place over a couple of weeks, allowing various local schools\u2019 differing spring break [[holiday]]s to coincide with one of the event's weeks. It has been a park tradition since 1984.\n* '''Festival Latino''' - In April, Hispanic and Latino [[Cultural heritage|heritage]] is celebrated throughout the park. The park is alive with arts, crafts, performances by bands and dancers, as well as authentic [[cuisine]] including [[fajitas]], [[sweet corn]], [[churros]] and [[tacos]]. The annual event started in 2006.\n* '''Fright Fest''' \u2013 Originally only one night in October called 'Fright Night', Fright Fest is the annual [[Halloween]] festival at Six Flags Over Texas. Fright Fest takes place throughout the month of October and features several specialized additions to the park. [[Haunted house]]s, decorated pathways, patrolling [[ghoul]]s and spooky music all contribute to the park's transformation into a giant 'scream' park.\n* '''[[Holiday in the Park]]''' \u2013 A tradition started in 1985, Holiday in the Park is now one of the park's most popular seasonal events as the park's season winds down towards the end of November and throughout December. Hundreds of thousands of [[Christmas lights (holiday decoration)|Christmas lights]] are strung around the park buildings and rides. An authentic snow hill is available for visitors to [[Toboggan|sled]] down. Festive holiday shows, arts and crafts, and delicious seasonal food also bring the holidays to Six Flags Over Texas.\n\n[[File:Sfot gotham city.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of \"[[Gotham City]]\"-themed section of the park. [[Texas State Highway 360|SH 360]] and [[Interstate 30 (Texas)|I-30]] intersect in the immediate background, showing the proximity of the park to local roadways.]]\n\n==Areas and attractions==\n* Guide to Rides & Attractions<ref>[http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/assets/pdf/SFOT_ADA.pdf Guide to Rides & Attractions]</ref>\n\n===Star Mall===\nThe Star Mall serves as the entry gate for Six Flags Over Texas. It was one of the original sections of the park when it opened in 1961. It is named for the large star-shaped fountain located in the section.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Silver Star Carousel]]'''\n|align=center|1963\n|Dentzel [[carousel]]\n|Last carousel built by William Dentzel. Originally located in Boomtown section, ride was removed for restoration in 1985 and reopened at current location in 1988.\n|\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Silver Star Carousel Stage \u2013 Located between the entrance and exit stairways to the Silver Star Carousel attraction, this multi-leveled stage showcases a variety of performances throughout the regular park operating season and during private park events as well. Although the stage is relatively small in size,{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=August 2017}} performances include dance spectacles during both Fright Fest and Holiday in the Park, school and private band recitals, and the daily Looney Tunes Party Rockin' Dance Party (March\u2013September).\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Pink Things\n* Flags Famous Funnel Cakes\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* $10 and Under\n\n'''Other guest services:'''\n* Guest services\n* Locker rental\n* Six Flags Season Pass Processing Center\n* Stroller rental\n* The [[Flash Pass]] Reservation Center\n* VIP Tours\n\n===Mexico & Spain===\nThe Mexico & Spain area consists of two sections both of which were originally part of the park in 1961. Both sections represent a flag that has flown over the state of Texas.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''El Sombrero'''\n|align=center|1965\n|[[Chance Rides]] [[Wipeout (ride)|trabant]]\n|Moved to new location in 2006.\n|\n|-\n|'''La Fiesta de las Tazas'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] [[teacups]]\n|Built in the former location of El Sombrero.\n|\n|-\n|'''Conquistador'''\n|align=center|1981\n|[[Intamin]] Bounty swinging ship\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[La Vibora]]'''\n|align=center|1986\n|[[Intamin]] Swiss Bob / [[Bobsled roller coaster]]\n|Ride was moved from [[Six Flags Magic Mountain]]. Originally named The Avalanche Bobsled.\n|[[File:SFOT Vibora 4 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[El Aserradero]]'''\n|align=center|1963\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] [[Log flume (ride)|Log flume]]\n|World's First Log Flume. Features two separate log flumes: Flume I (1963) & Flume II (1968). Flume 1 is currently Standing But Not Operating.\n|[[File:SixFlags-Log-Flume-5793.jpg|thumb|215x215px]]\n|-\n|'''El Diablo'''\n|align=center|2019\n|[[Larson International|Larson]] Giga Loop 100 Ft<ref>http://larsonintl.com/the-giga-loop-100-ft/</ref>\n|Originally called \"Lone Star Revolution,\" and planned to be placed in the tower section. The ride was recently renamed and moved to the Spain themed area.\n|[[File:El Diablo.jpg|alt=El Diablo|thumb|El Diablo]]\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Flags Funnel Cakes\n* Rancho de Pollo\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Six Flags Radio \u2013 located across from Indian Trading Village, guests can watch as specially-hired Six Flags Radio personalities\u2014referred to as DJs\u2014broadcast park-wide from inside the park's very own radio station.\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Casa de Six Flags\n* Mercado de la Plaza\n\n===Texas===\nThe Texas section of the park was another original section when the park opened in 1961. It is named after the Republic of Texas flag that once flew over the state.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Boot Scootin''''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] boot-themed Jump Around\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Chaparral Antique Cars'''\n|align=center|1962\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] antique cars\n|Entrance & Station relocated in 2011 and returned to its original entrance in 2016.\n|\n|-\n|'''Rodeo'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Huss Park Attractions|Huss]] [[Breakdance (ride)|Rodeo/Breakdance]]\n|Ride moved from [[Six Flags Great Adventure]].\n|[[File:Rodeo SFOT.jpg|alt=Rodeo|thumb|Rodeo]]\n|-\n|'''Sidewinder'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Eli Bridge]] [[Twist (ride)|Scrambler]]\n|Ride moved from [[Six Flags Astroworld]].\n|[[File:Sidewinder SFOT.jpg|alt=Sidewinder|thumb|Sidewinder]]\n|-\n|'''[[Six Flags & Texas Railroad]]'''\n|align=center|1961\n|{{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railways|narrow gauge]] train ride around the park.\n|Stations are the Texas Depot and Boomtown Depot.\n|[[File:Six Flags & Texas Railroad.jpg|alt=Six Flags & Texas Railroad|thumb|Six Flags & Texas Railroad]]\n|-\n|'''[[New Texas Giant]]'''\n|align=center|2011\n|Renovations by [[Rocky Mountain Construction]] / Hybrid roller coaster\n|It won the Golden Ticket Award for World's Best Wooden Roller Coaster of 1999. Closed for renovation in 2010. Reopened on April 22, 2011 as the world's first Rocky Mountain Construction (RMC) hybrid coaster. It won the Golden Ticket Award for Best New Coaster of 2011.\n|[[File:SFOT Giant 2 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Titan (Six Flags Over Texas)|Titan]]'''\n|align=center|2001\n|[[Giovanola]] / [[Hypercoaster]]\n|Tallest, fastest, and longest roller coaster in Texas.\n|[[File:SFOT Titan 18 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''Yosemite Sam And The Gold River Adventure'''\n|align=center|1994\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] Water [[Dark ride]]\n|Originally Opened in 1964 as Spee-Lunker's Cave Ride, name/theme changed in 1994.\u00a0It is currently [[Standing But Not Operating]].<ref>https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas/attractions/yosemite-sams-gold-river-adventure</ref><ref>http://www.screamscape.com/html/six_flags_over_texas.htm</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Back Porch Stage \u2013 This venue houses live bands during certain times of the year.\n* Courthouse Stage \u2013 This small, porch-like stage comes equipped with a splash zone for use in various period gunfighting performances during the summer.\n* Crazy Horse Saloon \u2013 The Crazy Horse Saloon has provided live entertainment for over 40 years, featuring cowboys and saloon girls. This is the oldest theater in the park.\n* Lone Star Gazebo \u2013 Directly adjacent to the Lone Star Theater entrance, this space now houses Six Flags Karaoke (March \u2013 late September).\n* Lone Star Theater \u2013 This venue usually houses specialty shows.\n* Lip Synch Challenge \u2013 Its when two people challenge each other to lip synch. It was originally in the Goodtimes Square section.\n[[File:Chaparral Antique Cars attraction at Six Flags Over Texas.JPG|right|thumb|200px|A woman and boy ride on the Chaparral Antique Cars attraction.]]\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* [[Coca-Cola Freestyle]]\n* E.G. Sugarwaters\n* [[Panda Express]]\n* Bubba's Texas Giant Hot Dogs\n* Newman's Corn Dogs\n* Miss Abby's Cookies and Ice Cream Shoppe\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Indian Trading Post\n* Texas Gift Shop\n* The Ole' Woodcutter Shop\n\n[[File:Wooden roller coaster txgi.jpg|right|300x|thumb|The Texas Giant before renovations]]\n[[File:The NEW Texas Giant.jpg|thumb|The Texas Giant after renovations]]\n[[File:Observationtower sfot.jpg|thumb|right|180px|The [[Oil Derrick (Six Flags Over Texas)|Oil Derrick]] observation tower]]\n[[File:SixFlagsWaterRide-3943.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Roaring Rapids river ride (2007)]]\n[[File:SupermanTower-5954.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Superman Tower of Power]]\n\n===Old South & France===\nThe Old South & France area consists of two sections both of which were originally part of the park in 1961. Both sections represent a flag that has flown over the state of Texas. The Old South was originally called The Confederacy and featured [[American Civil War reenactment|Civil War reenactments]], including performances representing the execution of a captured [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] spy.<ref name=wolcott/>\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Runaway Mountain]]'''\n|align=center|1996\n|[[Premier Rides]] / [[Enclosed roller coaster]]\n|Indoor coaster almost completely in the dark\n|[[File:Runaway Mountain.jpg|alt=Runaway Mountain|thumb|Runaway Mountain]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Mtn. 1 Edit.jpg|thumb|link=Special:FilePath/SFOT_Mtn._1_Edit.jpg]] -->\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* David Blackburn Southern Palace Theater - The largest indoor theater at Six Flags Over Texas. This venue houses all types of musical and dance shows.\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Cold Stone Creamery (formerly [[Ben & Jerrys]])\n* JB's Smokehouse Barbeque (formerly Gator McGee's Mountain Grill)\n* Primo's Pizzeria\n* Uncle Bub's Smokehouse\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Antique Photo Emporium\n* Les De Caricatures\n* M-Porium\n\n===USA===\nThe USA area of the park opened with the park in 1961. It was originally named the Modern Section, but still represented the United States flag that has flown over Texas.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride name\n!width=50|Year opened\n!Manufacturer and ride type\n!Other notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis|Justice League : Battle for Metropolis]]'''\n|align=center|2015\n|Interactive, 3-D, multi-motion base [[dark ride]]. Collaboration of [[Sally Dark Rides]], [[Alterface]], [[Oceaneering International]] and Pure Imagination Studios.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amusementtoday.com/2015/05/six-flags-over-texas-debuts-state-of-the-art-dark-ride/ |title=Six Flags Over Texas debuts state of the art dark ride |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=20 May 2015 |publisher=Amusement Today |access-date= 21 December 2015}}</ref>\n|Themed to Justice League. Debuted on May 19, 2015. Riders wear 3-D glasses and shoot at targets generated in real-time.\n|-\n|'''Aquaman: Power Wave'''\n|align=center|2020\n|[[Mack Rides]] PowerSplash coaster <ref>https://sixflags.com/overtexas/newsroom/newfor2020</ref>\n|Shuttle coaster with 3 launches, ending with a splashdown.\n|\n|}\n\n====Bugs Bunny Boomtown====\nIt is the children's area of the park. It originally opened in 1983 as [[Pac-Man]] Land. With the introduction of Looney Tunes characters to the park, it was renamed to Looney Tunes Land around 1985. In 2001, the area was renamed once again when it was expanded to include new attractions. It was renamed Bugs Bunny Boomtown for 2014.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Daffy Duck Bucket Blasters'''\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Zamperla]] Watermania\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Looney Tunes Adventure Camp'''\n|align=center|2014\n|Miracle Recreation Equipment play structure\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Marvin the Martian Space Rockets'''\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Zamperla]] Rocket Ride\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Speedy Gonzales' Truckin' Across America'''\n|align=center|1992\n|[[Zamperla]] Kiddie convoy/truck ride\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Sylvester & Tweety's State Fair-is Wheel'''\n|align=center|2001\n|[[Zamperla]] mini [[Ferris wheel]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Taz Tornado Swings'''\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Zamperla]] Lolly Swing\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Bugs Bunny Cloud Bouncer'''\n|align=center|2001\n|SBF/VISA group Happy Tower\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Wile E. Coyote's Grand Canyon Blaster]]'''\n|align=center|2001\n|[[Chance Rides]] Big Dipper / Junior coaster\n|\n|[[File:SFOT Coyote 10 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Coyote 8 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''Yosemite Sam's Texas Tea Cups'''\n|align=center|2001\n|SBF/VISA group mini [[teacups]]\n|\n|\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Bill's Lemonade\n* Granny's Grill\n* Six Flags All-American Cafe (Formerly USA Food Court)\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* ACME Rock-N-Rocket Shop (Closed at the end of 2014 to get ready for Justice League - Battle for Metropolis)\n* Cartoon Clubhouse\n* Looney Tunes Mall/Candy Corner\n* Studio 6F (Formerly Attitudes)\n\n'''Other Guest Services:'''\n* Baby Care\n* Lost Parents\n\n===Goodtimes Square===\nThe Goodtimes Square section of the park opened in 1973. Over the years, it took on a loose 1950s theme. Some of Goodtimes Square expanded to the Gotham City Section for the 2016-2017 season.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Cloud Bouncer'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] Samba balloon tower\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Judge Roy Scream]]'''\n|align=center|1980\n|Don Rosser & [[William Cobb|Bill Cobb]] / [[wooden roller coaster]]\n|Built outside main park area, along the park's entrance lake.\n|[[File:Judge Roy Scream SFOT.jpg|alt=Judge Roy Scream|thumb|Judge Roy Scream]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Scream 2 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''[[SkyScreamer|Texas SkyScreamer]]'''\n|align=center|2013\n|[[Funtime (manufacturer)|Funtime]] [[Swings (ride)|Star Flyer]]\n|Second Tallest Star Flyer in the world, standing 400&nbsp;ft.<ref name=\"TTS\"/>\n|[[File:Texas SkyScreamer SFOT.jpg|alt=Texas SkyScreamer|thumb|Texas SkyScreamer]]\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Majestic Theater - Originally the Krofft Puppet Circus & Goodtimes Theater, this venue houses all types of musical, dance and specialty shows.\n\n===Gotham City===\nGotham City opened in 1999 and is themed to the [[DC Comics]] [[Batman]] universe.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Batman: The Ride]]'''\n|align=center|1999\n|[[Bolliger & Mabillard]] / [[Inverted roller coaster]]\n|Is the only inverted coaster in the park. Trains were reversed for the 2014 season.\n|[[File:SFOT Batman 31 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Batman 3 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''Batwing'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] Telecombat\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Catwoman Whip'''\n|align=center|2016\n|[[Zamperla]] Endeavor\n|\n|[[File:Catwoman Whip.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''Harley Quinn Spinsanity'''\n|align=center|2018\n|ABC Rides Tourbillon\n|\n|[[File:HQS2.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Mr. Freeze (roller coaster)|Mr. Freeze: Reverse Blast]]''' <ref>[http://www.sixflags.com/overTexas/rides/MrFreezeReverseBlast.aspx \"Mr.Freeze Reverse Blast\"], Six Flags Over Texas website.</ref>\n|align=center|1998\n|[[Premier Rides]] [[linear motor|LIM]] / [[Launched roller coaster]]\n|Originally intended to open for the 1997 season, but problems with the LIM Launch system delayed opening until 1998. Trains were reversed and ride renamed to Mr. Freeze: Reverse Blast in 2012.\n|[[File:Mr Freeze SFOT.jpg|alt=Mr Freeze|thumb|Mr Freeze]]\n|-\n| '''[[The Joker (S&S Worldwide)|The Joker]]'''\n|align=center|2017\n|[[S&S Worldwide]] 4D Free Spin\n|\n|[[File:SFOT Joker 5 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Joker 13 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''[[The Riddler Revenge]]'''\n|align=center|2016\n|[[Zamperla]] Giant Discovery ride.\n|\n|[[File:Riddler's Revenge.jpg|thumb]]\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Gotham Snacks\n* [[Johnny Rockets]]\n[[File:Inverted coaster btr.jpg|thumb|right|[[Batman: The Ride]] at Six Flags Over Texas]]\n\n===Boomtown===\nThe Boomtown section opened in 1963. It is based on the Texas boomtowns that sprung up in Texas during the oil boom era.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''[[Mini Mine Train]]'''\n|align=center|1969\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] / [[Mine train roller coaster]]\n|Located next to the bigger Runaway Mine Train and Mr. Freeze. Track modified slightly in 1997 when Mr. Freeze was built next to/over parts of the track.\n|[[File:SFOT Mini 3 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Pandemonium (roller coaster)|Pandemonium]]''' <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-six-flags-retheme-20101122,0,3267615.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Brady | last=MacDonald | title=Six Flags amusement parks prepare for thematic makeovers | date=November 25, 2010}}</ref>\n|align=center|2008\n|Gerstlauer / [[Spinning roller coaster]]\n|Originally named \"Tony Hawk's Big Spin\".\n|[[File:Pandemonium SFOT.jpg|alt=Pandemonium|thumb|Pandemonium]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Big Spin 11 Edit.jpg|thumb|link=Special:FilePath/SFOT_Big_Spin_11_Edit.jpg]] -->\n|-\n|'''[[Mine Train (Six Flags Over Texas)|Runaway Mine Train]]'''\n|align=center|1966\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]] / [[Mine train roller coaster]]\n|First [[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow]] mine train coaster.\n|[[File:SFOT Mine 7 Edit.jpg|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''[[Six Flags & Texas Railroad]]'''\n|align=center|1961\n|{{RailGauge|3ft}} narrow gauge train ride around the park.\n|Stations are the Texas Depot and Boomtown Depot.\n|[[File:SFOT Train.jpg|alt=SFOT Train|thumb]]\n|-\n|'''The Gunslinger'''\n|align=center|1983\n|[[Chance Rides]] [[Yo-Yo (ride)|Yo-Yo]] swings ride\n|Ride was named Texas Tornado until 2007.\n|\n|}\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Dry Hole Charlie's\n* Dusty Dan's Waterin' Hole\n* Macho Nacho (Formally Goldminer's Diner)\n\n'''Merchandise:'''\n* Caricatures\n\n[[File:SixFlagsTrain-4027.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Six Flags & Texas Railroad (2007)]]\n[[File:SixFlagsKiddieSwing-4069.jpg|thumb|right|180px|The Gunslinger [[swing ride]] (2007)]]\n\n===Tower===\nThe Tower Section opened in 1969 and is named after the Oil Derrick tower location in the section.\n\n'''Attractions:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride Name\n!width=50|Year Opened\n!Manufacturer/Ride Type\n!Other Notes\n!Photo\n|-\n|'''Caddo Lake Barge'''\n|align=center|2006\n|[[Zamperla]] Rockin\u2019 Tug\n|\n|[[File:Caddo Lake Barge.jpg|alt=Caddo Lake Barge|thumb|Caddo Lake Barge]]\n|-\n|'''Dive Bomber Alley'''\n|align=center|1996\n|[[Skycoaster]]\n|Requires additional charge.\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Oil Derrick (Six Flags Over Texas)|Oil Derrick]]'''\n|align=center|1969\n|[[Intamin]] [[observation tower]]\n|Largest land-based [[oil derrick]] in the world standing 300&nbsp;ft tall.\n|[[File:Oil Derrick.jpg|alt=Oil Derrick|thumb|Oil Derrick]]\n|-\n|'''[[Roaring Rapids]]'''\n|align=center|1983\n|[[Intamin]] [[river rapids ride]]\n|Replaced Skull Island and LaSalle's Riverboat Adventure.\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Shock Wave (Six Flags Over Texas)|Shock Wave]]'''\n|align=center|1978\n|Schwarzkopf / Looping roller coaster\n|Steel coaster with two back-to-back vertical loops.\n|[[File:SFOT Shockwave 9 Edit.jpg|thumb]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SFOT Shockwave 5 Edit.jpg|thumb]] -->\n|-\n|'''Six Flags Speedway Go Karts'''\n|align=center|1999\n|J & J Amusements [[kart racing|go karts]]\n|Requires additional charge.\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Superman Tower Of Power]]'''\n|align=center|2003\n|3 [[S&S Worldwide]] [[Turbo Drop|Combo Towers]]\n|Tallest S&S Combo Tower in the world standing 325&nbsp;ft tall.\n|[[File:Superman Tower of Power SFOT.jpg|alt=Superman Tower of Power|thumb|Superman Tower of Power]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Superman Tower of Power (SFOT).jpg|thumb]] -->\n|}\n\n'''Entertainment:'''\n* Music Mill Amphitheater - The park's large outdoor amphitheater. This venue houses concerts and other live entertainment.\n* Texas Arena - This is the park's stunt show theater. In 2008, the Thursday Night Starburst Concert Series performed here.\n\n'''Dining:'''\n* Oliver's Tavern\n* Lone Star Twister Pretzels\n* Newman's Cafe\n* Flags Funnel Cakes (Formally Red River Dogs & Fries changed during Fright Fest 2014)\n\n==Former attractions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=126|Ride Name\n!width=50|Opened\n!width=50|Closed\n!Manufacturer\n!Ride Model/Type\n!Location\n!Notes\n\n!Photo\n\n|-\n|'''Aquaman Splashdown'''\n|align=center|1987\n|align=center|2019\n|[[Hopkins Rides]]\n|[[Shoot-the-Chutes]]\n|USA\n|Ride was named Splash Water Falls until 2007. Will be replaced by Aquaman Power Wave.\n|[[File:20190330 125959 Edit.jpg|alt=Aquaman Splashdown|thumb|Aquaman Splashdown]]\n|-\n|'''Big Bend'''\n|align=center|1971\n|align=center|1979\n|[[Anton Schwarzkopf|Schwarzkopf]]\n|Speed Racer\n|USA\n|Ride relocated to [[Six Flags St. Louis]], but was never re-assembled and was later scrapped.\n|\n|-\n|'''Bugs Bunny's Spirit of St. Louie'''\n|align=center|1976\n|align=center|2013\n|[[Zamperla]]\n|Mini airplane ride\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Caddo War Canoes'''\n|align=center|1962\n|align=center|1983\n|\n|[[Canoe|Canoe Ride]]\n|Boomtown\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Cinesphere Chevy Show'''\n|align=center|1969\n|align=center|1984\n|\n|[[70 mm film#Omnivision Cinema 180|Cinema 180]]\n|Old South\n|Current Lone Star Theater\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Daffy Duck's Capitol Tours'''\n|align=center|2001\n|align=center|2013\n|SBF/VISA group\n|Kiddie crazy bus ride\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Ferrocarril Fiesta Train'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1978\n|\n|[[Miniature Railway|Train Ride]]\n|Mexico\n|Updated in 1968\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Flashback'''\n|align=center|1989\n|align=center|2012\n|[[Vekoma]]\n|[[Boomerang (roller coaster)|Boomerang]]\n|Goodtimes Square\n|It was closed on September 3, 2012. Ride relocated to [[Six Flags St. Louis]], re-opened in 2013 as Boomerang\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Great Six Flags Air Racer'''\n|align=center|1984\n|align=center|1999\n|[[Intamin AG]]\n|Air Racer\n|Tower\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Harley Quinn Spinsanity'''\n|align=center|2006\n|align=center|2018\n|[[HUSS Park Attractions|Huss]]\n|Troika\n|Goodtimes Square\n|Removed before the start of the 2018 season. The ride was originally named Crazy Legs from 2006-2016. Ride relocated from [[Six Flags Astroworld]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''La Cucaracha'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1964\n|[[Allan Herschell Company|Allan Herschell]]\n|[[Wild Mouse roller coaster|Wild Mouse]]\n|Mexico\n|Originally named Sidewinder and was located in the USA section in 1961. Name changed and moved to Mexico section in 1962.\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Las Cocheses Cabras Goat Cart'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1963\n|\n|\n|Mexico\n|Goat powered cart ride\n\n|\n|-\n|'''LaSalle's Riverboat Expedition'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1982\n|\n|[[Water ride|Guided Old Mill]]\n|France\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Little Dixie Carousel'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1974\n|\n|[[Carousel|Animal Powered Carousel]]\n|Old South\n|Also known as Flying Jenny\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Los Conquistadores Mule Pack Ride Coronado Trek'''<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rcreride.com/html/sfot_Map.html |title= 1961 Map of Six Flags Over Texas  |publisher= American Coaster Enthusiasts |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1962\n|\n|\n|Spain\n|Although titled \"mule pack ride,\" guests actually rode burros and were led by a host dressed as conquistador, riding a horse.<ref name=RC117/>\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Michigan J. Frog's Tinsel Town Revue'''\n|align=center|1985\n|align=center|2013\n|[[Zamperla]]\n|Mini [[swinger (ride)|swinger ride]]\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Overland Butterfield Stagecoach'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1967\n|\n|[[Stagecoach]]\n|Old South\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Rotoriculous'''\n|align=center|1975\n|align=center|1988\n|[[Reverchon Industries|Reverchon]]\n|Himalaya\n|Goodtimes Square\n|Ride was enclosed\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Route 66 Bumper Cars'''\n|align=center|2001\n|align=center|2013\n|SBF/VISA group\n|Mini [[bumper cars]]\n|Looney Tunes USA\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Skull Island'''\n|align=center|1961\n|align=center|1982\n|\n|[[Playground]]\n|Skull Island\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Sky Hook'''\n|align=center|1963\n|align=center|1968\n|\n|Sky Crane\n|Boomtown\n|An observation ride adapted from a cargo crane by Von Roll of Switzerland.<ref name=RC117/> Ride relocated to [[Six Flags Over Georgia]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Spee-Lunker's Cave'''\n|align=center|1964\n|align=center|1991\n|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n|[[Dark ride|Floating Dark Ride]]\n|Texas\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Spindletop'''\n|align=center|1967\n|align=center|1989\n|[[Chance Rides]]\n|[[Rotor (ride)|Rotor]]\n|Goodtimes Square/Texas\n|Relocated to [[Frontier City]] where it's currently operating and renamed Terrible Twister and then Tumbleweed in 2014.\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Spinnaker'''\n|align=center|1977\n|align=center|1995\n|[[Anton Schwarzkopf|Schwarzkopf GmbH]]\n|[[Enterprise (ride)|Enterprise]]\n|Tower\n|Relocated to [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Texas Chute Out]]'''\n|align=center|1976\n|align=center|2012\n|[[Intamin AG]]\n|Parachute Tower\n|Goodtimes Square\n|Demolished on October 10, 2012. Replaced by [[Texas SkyScreamer|SkyScreamer]]\n\n|\n|-\n|'''Tower Slide'''\n|align=center|1969\n|align=center|1976\n|\n|[[Fun Slide]]\n|Tower Section\n|\n|\n|-\n<ref>guidetosfot.com/rides/oilderrick/</ref>\n|'''Virtual Quest'''\n|align=center|2001\n|align=center|2005\n|\n|[[Virtual reality]]\n|Goodtimes Square\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''ACME Rock-n-Rocket'''\n|align=center|2006\n|align=center|2014\n|[[Intamin AG]]\n|[[Looping Starship]]\n|USA\n|Closed on August 24, 2014. Replaced by Justice League:Battle for Metropolis\n|\n|-\n|}\n* '''Turbo Bungy''' - [[bungee cord|bungee]] [[trampoline]]\n* '''Helicopter Rides''' - [[helicopter]] tours above the park\n* '''Astro-Lift''' - A [[Von Roll Holding|Von Roll]] [[Von Roll Holding#VonRoll type 101s ever built|type 101 aerial ropeway]] across the park\n* '''Humble's Happy Motoring Freeway Track I & II''' - [[Arrow Dynamics]] guide-limited auto ride\n* '''Jet Set''' - individual controlled mini jets. Intamin's very first ride.<ref name=RC117/>\n* '''Missile Chaser''' - classic [[Twist (ride)|scrambler]] that was moved to [[Six Flags Magic Mountain]]\n* '''Petting Zoo''' - [[petting zoo]]\n* '''Wildcatter''' ([[Intamin]] [[freefall (ride)|1st-Generation Intamin Freefall]]) - originally called Texas Cliffhanger; opened in 1982; located in USA \"Boomtown\" section. The ride was demolished in October 2007.\n* '''[[SpongeBob SquarePants 4-D|SpongeBob SquarePants: The Ride]]''' ([[motion simulator]] theater) - opened in 2004; located in USA section. Removed after 2007 season.\n* '''Bumper Cars''' (Soli [[bumper cars]]) - opened in 1973; located in Goodtimes Square section. Closed in August 2007 for Fright Fest and remained closed after the 2007 season.\n* '''[[Crazy Legs (amusement ride)|Crazy Legs]]''' ([[Eyerly Aircraft]] Monster) - opened in 1973; closed after the 1980 season.\n* '''Porky Pig Magic Wheel''' - was a typical [[Eli Bridge|Eli Bridge Company]] model [[Ferris wheel]] located in Looney Tunes USA where the current \"Fair-is Wheel\" is located.\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn August 2017, in response to the controversial [[Unite the Right rally]] that was held in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], the park replaced its six flags (which had included the [[Flags of the Confederate States of America#First flag: the \"Stars and Bars\" (1861\u20131863)|original Confederate flag]]) with six American flags. A representative of the park told [[KXAS-TV]], \"We always choose to focus on celebrating the things that unite us versus those that divide us. As such, we have changed the flag displays in our park to feature American flags.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2017/08/18/six-flags-confederate-flags/|title=Six Flags Pulls Down Confederate Flags|last1=Morris|first1=David Z.|date=August 18, 2017|work=Fortune|access-date=August 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2017/08/18/six-flags-over-texas-removes-confederate-flag-reversing-earlier-decision.html|title=Six Flags Over Texas removes Confederate flag, reversing earlier decision &#124; Fox News|date=August 18, 2017|website=FoxNews.com|access-date=August 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Trains}}\n* [[Six Flags Hurricane Harbor]]\n* [[List of amusement parks in the Americas]]\n* [[Incidents at Six Flags parks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n* Jordan, Scott L. [https://archive.is/20130103214903/http://www.mouseplanet.com/scott/072400.htm MousePlanet - This Old Park]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n* McCown, Davis. [http://parktimes.com ParkTimes]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n* Rogers, Joel A. [http://www.coastergallery.com/2001T/SFOT.html CoasterGallery.com]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040922014822/http://www.sixflags.com/media_info.asp Six Flags - Media Info]. Retrieved September 21, 2004.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.sixflags.com/overtexas Six Flags Over Texas official website]\n* {{RCDB|4531}}\n\n{{Six Flags}}\n{{Six Flags Over Texas}}\n{{Arlington, Texas}}\n\n[[Category:Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Texas]]\n[[Category:Six Flags amusement parks|Over Texas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Tarrant County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in Texas]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Six Flags Over Texas| ]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Tarrant County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1961]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "change status to \"operating\" as we don't include temporary closures perWP:NOTNEWS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six_Flags_Over_Texas"}
